8
00:00:17.10 --> 00:00:19.18
in the following citation.

9
00:00:19.18 --> 00:00:23.38
For heroic achievement as a pilot of jet aircraft

10
00:00:23.38 --> 00:00:27.94
while attached to fighter squadron 142,

11
00:00:27.94 --> 00:00:30.90
embarked in USS Constellation.

12
00:00:30.90 --> 00:00:33.50
On 14 January, 1970,

13
00:00:33.50 --> 00:00:35.70
Lieutenant Coppell flew the wing aircraft

14
00:00:35.70 --> 00:00:38.62
of a two-plane attack mission in Southeast Asia.

15
00:00:38.62 --> 00:00:41.86
Despite heavy anti-aircraft fire in the area,

16
00:00:41.86 --> 00:00:44.18
he placed all of his bombs on target,

17
00:00:44.18 --> 00:00:46.82
resulting in five enemy trucks destroyed

18
00:00:46.82 --> 00:00:51.56
and many secondary explosions and many enemy casualties.

19
00:00:52.46 --> 00:00:54.38
His professional determination in spite of

20
00:00:54.38 --> 00:00:57.92
heavy anti-aircraft fire and adverse weather conditions

21
00:00:57.92 --> 00:01:00.42
resulted in a substantial damage

22
00:01:00.42 --> 00:01:03.42
to the enemy's logistics efforts.

23
00:01:03.42 --> 00:01:06.70
Lieutenant Coppell's superb airmanship, courage,

24
00:01:06.70 --> 00:01:10.26
and devotion to duty reflected great credit upon himself

25
00:01:10.26 --> 00:01:13.18
and weren't keeping with the highest traditions

26
00:01:13.18 --> 00:01:16.34
of the United States Naval Service.

27
00:01:16.34 --> 00:01:20.46
The combat distinguishing device is authorized

28
00:01:20.46 --> 00:01:24.18
for the secretary M.F. Weisner,

29
00:01:24.18 --> 00:01:29.16
Vice Admiral, United States Navy.

30
00:01:29.16 --> 00:01:33.26
And that is a citation that represents

31
00:01:33.26 --> 00:01:35.18
the types of missions that were flown

32
00:01:35.18 --> 00:01:38.22
by Navy fighters day after day,

33
00:01:38.22 --> 00:01:42.54
night after night, week after week, month after month,

34
00:01:42.54 --> 00:01:44.30
year after year.

35
00:01:44.30 --> 00:01:45.90
Those were the type of missions

36
00:01:45.90 --> 00:01:53.40
that resulted in solid battle damage to the enemy,

37
00:01:54.70 --> 00:01:59.70
but also resulted in 532 aircraft lost in combat.

38
00:02:00.70 --> 00:02:05.70
401 aviators killed, 64 missing, 179 captured,

39
00:02:08.10 --> 00:02:09.54
who became prisoners of war.

