Whatever.

269
00:12:00.22 --> 00:12:02.38
So the rock and roll thing was not your scene?

270
00:12:02.38 --> 00:12:06.06
Not until the California, the British invasion

271
00:12:06.06 --> 00:12:07.58
and California.

272
00:12:07.58 --> 00:12:09.06
And that was all together different.

273
00:12:09.06 --> 00:12:10.74
Okay, we'll get there.

274
00:12:10.74 --> 00:12:14.82
So you graduate from high school, 1959.

275
00:12:14.82 --> 00:12:16.86
So you lived through the Korean War as well?

276
00:12:16.86 --> 00:12:18.34
I remember it well.

277
00:12:18.34 --> 00:12:20.50
I remember being in Boy Scout camp

278
00:12:20.50 --> 00:12:23.34
when they announced the armistice

279
00:12:24.34 --> 00:12:29.34
had just been signed that morning or whenever it was.

280
00:12:30.38 --> 00:12:31.22
That was a big deal.

281
00:12:31.22 --> 00:12:32.50
Everybody sheared.

282
00:12:32.50 --> 00:12:35.02
But you still didn't get the impression

283
00:12:35.02 --> 00:12:36.82
that that was something that you might do one day?

284
00:12:36.82 --> 00:12:37.74
No, no.

285
00:12:37.74 --> 00:12:41.54
There was no military tradition in the family at all,

286
00:12:41.54 --> 00:12:46.54
except for a grand uncle, Maximum Nice Guy,

287
00:12:47.06 --> 00:12:52.06
who was a graduate of the same college

288
00:12:52.30 --> 00:12:55.98
as Donald Trump graduated, still exists

289
00:12:55.98 --> 00:13:00.38
at New York State Military Academy, I think it's called.

290
00:13:00.38 --> 00:13:04.98
But he graduated in 1936 or something like that.

291
00:13:04.98 --> 00:13:09.98
And he was part of the last combat cavalry regiment

292
00:13:10.90 --> 00:13:13.54
in the United States Army.

293
00:13:13.54 --> 00:13:17.26
And I was disbanded, I think in 1939,

294
00:13:17.26 --> 00:13:19.50
as the storm clouds were gathering

295
00:13:19.50 --> 00:13:21.42
and they disbanded that unit.

296
00:13:21.42 --> 00:13:25.34
But that was officers with real swords

297
00:13:25.34 --> 00:13:28.18
and two horses each and all the rest

298
00:13:28.18 --> 00:13:30.66
of everything else about that.

299
00:13:30.66 --> 00:13:34.54
But that was a combat unit, not a display unit.

300
00:13:34.54 --> 00:13:36.02
And it was the last one.

301
00:13:36.02 --> 00:13:39.62
He wound up in Iceland for the duration of the war,

302
00:13:39.62 --> 00:13:42.46
deriding the whole experience.

303
00:13:42.46 --> 00:13:45.62
But I only realized in my grown-up days

304
00:13:45.62 --> 00:13:49.74
that if Hitler had won the Battle of Britain,

305
00:13:49.74 --> 00:13:51.54
Iceland was next.

306
00:13:51.54 --> 00:13:54.62
And they probably, no doubt knew that,

307
00:13:54.62 --> 00:13:59.02
but they all, I went to a reunion with him at one point

308
00:13:59.02 --> 00:14:02.78
and they all derided their experience there and so forth.

309
00:14:02.78 --> 00:14:04.82
But they would have been the first to be killed

310
00:14:04.82 --> 00:14:09.82
and the first super German raid on Iceland

311
00:14:10.54 --> 00:14:11.82
to flatten the place.

312
00:14:11.82 --> 00:14:14.18
Yeah, we used to get a similar thing in the SEAL teams

313
00:14:14.18 --> 00:14:16.82
where you'd get some platoons would be going over

314
00:14:16.82 --> 00:14:19.06
to Iraq or Afghanistan.

315
00:14:19.06 --> 00:14:23.18
And some other platoons would be going to like Guam

316
00:14:23.18 --> 00:14:25.30
or somewhere where there's no war going on.

317
00:14:25.30 --> 00:14:27.70
And of course, all the guys that are,

318
00:14:27.70 --> 00:14:30.06
get sent to Guam are just angry

319
00:14:30.06 --> 00:14:32.06
that they can't be in Iraq or Afghanistan.

320
00:14:32.06 --> 00:14:34.22
And meanwhile, the guys in Iraq or Afghanistan

321
00:14:34.22 --> 00:14:37.22
are freezing or sweating to death

322
00:14:37.22 --> 00:14:38.46
or to get shot at or whatever.

323
00:14:38.46 --> 00:14:41.74
Yeah, they use real bullets here and stuff like that.

324
00:14:41.74 --> 00:14:42.58
But that's what, you know,

325
00:14:42.58 --> 00:14:44.62
that's what people join the SEAL teams for.

326
00:14:44.62 --> 00:14:45.46
Yeah.

327
00:14:45.46 --> 00:14:48.14
And apparently the horse cavalry as well.

328
00:14:48.14 --> 00:14:50.54
Yeah, it was for real.

329
00:14:50.54 --> 00:14:53.98
Swords and the whole deal with those guys.

330
00:14:53.98 --> 00:14:56.82
And he was a wonderful man, wonderful man.

331
00:14:57.74 --> 00:15:01.82
When sisters were born, I got farmed out with him twice

332
00:15:01.82 --> 00:15:02.94
in the summertime.

333
00:15:02.94 --> 00:15:07.94
And he worked in Lower New York State Binghamton

334
00:15:09.10 --> 00:15:11.42
and Elmira, those places around there.

335
00:15:11.42 --> 00:15:16.42
And he had grand aunts who had a truncated farm there.

336
00:15:16.58 --> 00:15:20.02
And he farmed me out with them.

337
00:15:20.02 --> 00:15:21.10
You're just slave labor.

338
00:15:21.10 --> 00:15:22.50
And I had fun.

339
00:15:22.50 --> 00:15:27.50
I had kid fun being a kid with cornfields and ponds

340
00:15:27.50 --> 00:15:31.66
and stuff like that all over the place there.

341
00:15:31.66 --> 00:15:32.90
And then where'd you end up?

342
00:15:32.90 --> 00:15:34.78
So where'd you end up going to college?

343
00:15:34.78 --> 00:15:37.34
I went to Albright College in Reading, PA.

344
00:15:39.42 --> 00:15:41.18
Commuter for me.

345
00:15:41.18 --> 00:15:43.34
Very small college at that time,

346
00:15:43.34 --> 00:15:45.58
850 students at that time.

347
00:15:45.58 --> 00:15:48.94
And now it's about 12 or 1300,

348
00:15:48.94 --> 00:15:51.26
maybe a little bit more than that.

349
00:15:51.26 --> 00:15:54.02
But wonderful teachers there.

350
00:15:54.02 --> 00:15:55.26
Absolutely wonderful.

351
00:15:55.26 --> 00:15:58.58
Especially the man, but one notable woman

352
00:15:58.58 --> 00:16:01.98
who was a pacifist of all things.

353
00:16:01.98 --> 00:16:04.26
But she was absolutely a wonderful woman.

354
00:16:04.26 --> 00:16:05.10
And...

355
00:16:05.10 --> 00:16:08.18
How come she left such a big impression on you?

356
00:16:08.18 --> 00:16:10.38
Because she was so straight.

357
00:16:10.38 --> 00:16:12.50
I'd never met a woman quite like that.

358
00:16:12.50 --> 00:16:17.50
She was straightforward and thoughtful and aggressive.

359
00:16:18.98 --> 00:16:21.14
I like a woman who is my wife.

360
00:16:21.14 --> 00:16:26.14
She tells you what's on her mind immediately.

361
00:16:27.22 --> 00:16:29.10
And she was that way, I guess.

362
00:16:29.10 --> 00:16:30.38
And she was a professor there?

363
00:16:30.38 --> 00:16:31.22
Yeah, she was.

364
00:16:31.22 --> 00:16:32.06
What was she teaching?

365
00:16:32.06 --> 00:16:34.74
English, English and speech.

366
00:16:34.74 --> 00:16:39.74
And she changed with her professional abilities and so forth.

367
00:16:43.18 --> 00:16:48.06
And I remember sitting there arguing with her silently.

368
00:16:48.06 --> 00:16:53.06
No, a ten minute lecture about using the atomic bomb

369
00:16:54.14 --> 00:16:56.82
in Japan, she was opposed to that.

370
00:16:56.82 --> 00:17:01.82
And I don't think she had read notably or widely enough

371
00:17:03.14 --> 00:17:05.26
about all that.

372
00:17:05.26 --> 00:17:09.74
And I had at that point, as opposed to that.

373
00:17:09.74 --> 00:17:12.58
But still, I thought she was really great.

374
00:17:14.02 --> 00:17:16.70
Point of view sort of thing.

375
00:17:16.70 --> 00:17:18.58
What were you studying?

376
00:17:18.58 --> 00:17:23.58
I was an econ major, not business, economics

377
00:17:24.62 --> 00:17:26.06
and minor in history.

378
00:17:27.42 --> 00:17:31.62
And had some fabulous teachers there.

379
00:17:32.98 --> 00:17:37.98
A guy named Wilbur Gingrich who was a genuinely world famous

380
00:17:39.74 --> 00:17:43.30
Greek scholar and biblical scholar.

381
00:17:43.30 --> 00:17:46.86
A couple of other guys that nobody ever heard of,

382
00:17:46.86 --> 00:17:48.46
but a wonderful man.

383
00:17:48.46 --> 00:17:53.46
And a crazy guy who loved to teach European

384
00:17:56.18 --> 00:17:58.02
and Russian history.

385
00:17:58.02 --> 00:17:59.70
And I took him for Russian.

386
00:17:59.70 --> 00:18:01.94
Don't take him for God's sakes.

387
00:18:01.94 --> 00:18:04.10
You've got a D out of that.

388
00:18:04.10 --> 00:18:07.86
And he'll blither you and you can't write fast enough.

389
00:18:07.86 --> 00:18:10.18
And his class, his name was,

390
00:18:10.18 --> 00:18:15.18
Gingrich was the biblical scholar, a Greek scholar.

391
00:18:18.78 --> 00:18:19.62
Can you believe it?

392
00:18:19.62 --> 00:18:20.46
His name escapes me.

393
00:18:20.46 --> 00:18:22.54
But at any rate, Kistler.

394
00:18:22.54 --> 00:18:26.82
And they said, you'll get a D out of his class

395
00:18:26.82 --> 00:18:29.50
because you can't write fast enough and stuff like that.

396
00:18:29.50 --> 00:18:33.34
But he was something, he smoked continuously.

397
00:18:35.34 --> 00:18:37.90
And always had the window open and the butts went out

398
00:18:37.90 --> 00:18:40.62
of the window and he'd torch up another one.

399
00:18:40.62 --> 00:18:43.02
But he was really something.

400
00:18:43.02 --> 00:18:44.94
What'd you get in the class?

401
00:18:44.94 --> 00:18:47.86
B, all of six in the class.

402
00:18:47.86 --> 00:18:52.62
So at some point you got more into school than you were

403
00:18:52.62 --> 00:18:54.14
when you were in grammar school or whatever.

404
00:18:54.14 --> 00:18:56.86
Yeah, no, because I had smart people

405
00:18:56.86 --> 00:18:58.70
who were just smarter than I was.

406
00:18:58.70 --> 00:19:02.10
And how'd you put it?

407
00:19:02.10 --> 00:19:04.46
My parents weren't really educated, if you will.

408
00:19:04.46 --> 00:19:07.30
My mother had a college degree from NYU,

409
00:19:07.30 --> 00:19:10.06
but I think she skated as much as she could.

410
00:19:10.06 --> 00:19:13.42
And my dad, they kicked him out of grade school,

411
00:19:13.42 --> 00:19:18.42
yeah, out of school when he was after 10th grade,

412
00:19:18.42 --> 00:19:21.26
I think, because he was done.

413
00:19:21.26 --> 00:19:24.86
They did that at that time in the 20s.

414
00:19:24.86 --> 00:19:28.50
So both of them wanted me to be educated.

415
00:19:28.50 --> 00:19:32.58
And so it was interesting to be in the company

416
00:19:32.58 --> 00:19:34.26
of genuinely educated people.

417
00:19:34.26 --> 00:19:36.42
And I didn't catch fire at first

418
00:19:36.42 --> 00:19:38.58
by the time I was a junior.

419
00:19:38.58 --> 00:19:42.58
I understood that this is really an experience.

420
00:19:42.58 --> 00:19:48.70
You can get interesting things out of these people.

421
00:19:48.70 --> 00:19:51.30
By the time I was a senior, I didn't want to leave.

422
00:19:51.30 --> 00:19:54.86
Because you get to talk as a grown-up

423
00:19:54.86 --> 00:19:56.78
with these grown-ups who listen to you

424
00:19:56.78 --> 00:20:00.38
and then tell you things you had never conceived of before

425
00:20:00.38 --> 00:20:01.98
and stuff like that.

426
00:20:01.98 --> 00:20:06.94
So I had a good time in college until they kicked me out.

427
00:20:06.94 --> 00:20:08.94
At what point did you start looking at the military

428
00:20:08.94 --> 00:20:12.22
as a legitimate option for you?

429
00:20:12.22 --> 00:20:15.62
Not until I was about to graduate.

430
00:20:15.62 --> 00:20:19.94
And back in the good old days, my dad worked.

431
00:20:19.94 --> 00:20:22.30
He was a New Yorker, New Yorker, New Yorker,

432
00:20:22.30 --> 00:20:25.74
but he got a job in Redding, Pennsylvania.

433
00:20:25.74 --> 00:20:27.18
And it was a shock to all of us.

434
00:20:27.18 --> 00:20:28.94
I didn't want to leave the school I was in.

435
00:20:28.94 --> 00:20:31.38
I was going to Progles.

436
00:20:31.38 --> 00:20:32.66
So this is back in high school?

437
00:20:32.66 --> 00:20:34.14
Yeah.

438
00:20:34.14 --> 00:20:37.70
I was two years into Chamonaut High School in Long Island,

439
00:20:37.70 --> 00:20:41.98
which is by entrance exams and tuition.

440
00:20:41.98 --> 00:20:43.34
And I liked it there.

441
00:20:43.34 --> 00:20:45.98
I was doing a little bit better, a little bit better.

442
00:20:45.98 --> 00:20:47.86
But I didn't want to leave.

443
00:20:47.86 --> 00:20:50.70
And he came home and said he'd been offered a job

444
00:20:50.70 --> 00:20:51.86
in Redding, Pennsylvania.

445
00:20:51.86 --> 00:20:54.58
Where is that?

446
00:20:54.58 --> 00:20:58.14
We were New Yorkers, New Yorkers.

447
00:20:58.14 --> 00:20:59.46
I can do the accent, too.

448
00:20:59.46 --> 00:21:01.62
And of course, when you get to Pennsylvania,

449
00:21:01.62 --> 00:21:05.54
the kids make endless fun of you because of your accent

450
00:21:05.54 --> 00:21:06.30
and stuff.

451
00:21:06.30 --> 00:21:09.46
But at any rate, where was I in this?

452
00:21:09.46 --> 00:21:12.06
We're just trying to figure out, at what point did you

453
00:21:12.06 --> 00:21:13.66
think the military might be an option?

454
00:21:13.66 --> 00:21:20.30
I could go downtown Redding and go up the fire tower staircase

455
00:21:20.30 --> 00:21:24.06
and plop in the chair in my dad's office.

456
00:21:24.06 --> 00:21:25.94
And he said, so what are you going to do?

457
00:21:25.94 --> 00:21:27.54
You're going to graduate here.

458
00:21:27.54 --> 00:21:29.70
I said, I don't know.

459
00:21:29.70 --> 00:21:34.14
He said, have you considered maybe the government would

460
00:21:34.14 --> 00:21:36.22
teach you how to fly in one of the services?

461
00:21:36.22 --> 00:21:38.42
And I, they don't take guys like me.

462
00:21:38.42 --> 00:21:40.02
He said, they surely do.

463
00:21:40.02 --> 00:21:46.02
2020s and good shape, nothing wrong with it.

464
00:21:46.02 --> 00:21:48.66
So I applied to the Navy guy.

465
00:21:48.66 --> 00:21:53.54
And he was an embarrassment.

466
00:21:53.54 --> 00:21:59.54
Overweight, feet up on the desk, didn't seem to care about

467
00:21:59.54 --> 00:21:59.98
anything.

468
00:21:59.98 --> 00:22:01.38
I filled out all his paperwork.

469
00:22:01.38 --> 00:22:03.22
And he never got back to me.

470
00:22:03.22 --> 00:22:04.46
Went to the Air Force guy.

471
00:22:04.46 --> 00:22:09.22
And he was close to his quota, probably.

472
00:22:09.22 --> 00:22:11.10
He drove me around.

473
00:22:11.10 --> 00:22:13.46
You have to go here and fill out these.

474
00:22:13.46 --> 00:22:16.54
I'll help you fill out the form.

475
00:22:16.54 --> 00:22:17.90
And the Air Force took me.

476
00:22:17.90 --> 00:22:25.26
So, but the, when was the question?

477
00:22:25.26 --> 00:22:26.54
Well, that was the question.

478
00:22:26.54 --> 00:22:29.02
The question was, how did you first get the idea of how to

479
00:22:29.02 --> 00:22:29.02
fly?

480
00:22:29.02 --> 00:22:31.74
My dad said, see if you learn how to fly.

481
00:22:31.74 --> 00:22:33.18
And he didn't know how to fly.

482
00:22:33.18 --> 00:22:35.90
So did they have like a contract that made you a pilot?

483
00:22:35.90 --> 00:22:39.74
Was that part of the enlistment process?

484
00:22:39.74 --> 00:22:43.98
They only said, we like everything you do.

485
00:22:43.98 --> 00:22:49.70
Now you have to fill out a preference sheet.

486
00:22:49.70 --> 00:22:51.98
And you can put whatever you like in there.

487
00:22:51.98 --> 00:22:55.94
We suggest this list of stuff over here.

488
00:22:55.94 --> 00:23:00.02
And then you make them one, two, and three choices.

489
00:23:00.02 --> 00:23:03.42
I said, well, I want to be a pilot.

490
00:23:03.42 --> 00:23:07.22
Because that's what I'm doing this whole thing for.

491
00:23:07.22 --> 00:23:09.86
He said, well, most people put in navigator for second and

492
00:23:09.86 --> 00:23:13.34
then something like, I don't know, auxiliary

493
00:23:13.34 --> 00:23:15.22
aviation or something like that.

494
00:23:15.22 --> 00:23:17.26
I said, well, that's not why I'm here.

495
00:23:17.26 --> 00:23:20.94
So I put pilot, pilot, pilot, one, two, three.

496
00:23:20.94 --> 00:23:24.46
Funny thing too, the B-52 squadron I was later in, was a

497
00:23:24.46 --> 00:23:26.98
guy from my college class.

498
00:23:26.98 --> 00:23:30.14
And I said, Danny, what are you doing here as a navigator?

499
00:23:30.14 --> 00:23:33.18
He said, well, they told me, put pilot first, navigator

500
00:23:33.18 --> 00:23:34.86
second.

501
00:23:34.86 --> 00:23:37.54
I said, you don't wear glasses or anything.

502
00:23:37.54 --> 00:23:40.50
He said, well, that's what they took me as.

503
00:23:40.50 --> 00:23:42.90
I said, well, I didn't want to rub it in.

504
00:23:42.90 --> 00:23:45.58
So I just let it alone.

505
00:23:45.58 --> 00:23:48.46
So what was your indoctrination to the Air Force then?

506
00:23:48.46 --> 00:23:53.86
I went to their OCS in San Antonio.

507
00:23:53.86 --> 00:23:57.74
It's not at Lackland.

508
00:23:57.74 --> 00:23:59.78
I think they called it the Medina base.

509
00:23:59.78 --> 00:24:01.94
It's nearby.

510
00:24:01.94 --> 00:24:02.90
And I went through that.

511
00:24:02.90 --> 00:24:04.18
That's three months.

512
00:24:04.18 --> 00:24:06.34
Was it a shock to your system?

513
00:24:06.34 --> 00:24:08.70
Were you wondering why the hell you did this?

514
00:24:08.70 --> 00:24:09.90
Well, I was fortunate.

515
00:24:09.90 --> 00:24:15.42
There were several previous enlisted guys there.

516
00:24:15.42 --> 00:24:17.86
And I thought, they know the ropes.

517
00:24:17.86 --> 00:24:19.26
Do whatever they do.

518
00:24:19.26 --> 00:24:22.06
So that's what I did.

519
00:24:22.06 --> 00:24:26.30
And then they said, if you play a musical instrument, put

520
00:24:26.30 --> 00:24:27.42
your name on this list.

521
00:24:27.42 --> 00:24:28.74
And I said, no, no.

522
00:24:28.74 --> 00:24:31.98
Guy told me, don't volunteer for anything.

523
00:24:31.98 --> 00:24:33.66
Before I went in.

524
00:24:33.66 --> 00:24:38.10
So I found out the guy was running this thing.

525
00:24:38.10 --> 00:24:42.14
He loves to have live music for any parades that he has.

526
00:24:42.14 --> 00:24:44.30
And if you can play a musical, get your name on it.

527
00:24:44.30 --> 00:24:45.50
I did.

528
00:24:45.50 --> 00:24:46.30
So there were.

529
00:24:46.30 --> 00:24:47.58
What instrument did you play?

530
00:24:47.58 --> 00:24:50.22
I played the trumpet and cornet.

531
00:24:50.22 --> 00:24:51.34
I played baritone.

532
00:24:51.34 --> 00:24:55.66
I can play alto, or French horn, or any of those.

533
00:24:55.66 --> 00:24:58.34
But I dropped that for a long time in midlife.

534
00:24:58.34 --> 00:25:00.46
I'm back into it now.

535
00:25:00.46 --> 00:25:04.10
Anyway, you got out of everything.

536
00:25:04.10 --> 00:25:09.98
You straightened up your digs and your bed and whatnot.

537
00:25:09.98 --> 00:25:14.78
And when the Saturday morning inspection happened,

538
00:25:14.78 --> 00:25:16.50
we had rehearsal.

539
00:25:16.50 --> 00:25:21.22
And that was they, if you will, all knew that.

540
00:25:21.22 --> 00:25:23.94
So this is, what, 1963?

541
00:25:23.94 --> 00:25:26.30
No, no, 65.

542
00:25:26.30 --> 00:25:27.74
January 65.

543
00:25:27.74 --> 00:25:31.54
Because, see, I graduated in August

544
00:25:31.54 --> 00:25:37.26
because I was having too much fun by that point in college.

545
00:25:37.26 --> 00:25:39.58
You ought to take that professor's history course.

546
00:25:39.58 --> 00:25:41.18
He's really interesting.

547
00:25:41.18 --> 00:25:44.18
And you should take compared to the economic systems,

548
00:25:44.18 --> 00:25:45.46
because you should do that.

549
00:25:45.46 --> 00:25:47.90
And I didn't have enough credits.

550
00:25:47.90 --> 00:25:49.46
I had two.

551
00:25:49.46 --> 00:25:53.30
If you needed 150, I had 175.

552
00:25:53.30 --> 00:25:56.30
But you don't have enough in your major or in your minor.

553
00:25:56.30 --> 00:26:00.06
You took that course and you got good grading.

554
00:26:00.06 --> 00:26:00.58
And you're right.

555
00:26:00.58 --> 00:26:03.46
So I wound up graduating in August.

556
00:26:03.46 --> 00:26:06.06
But how did you get into that?

557
00:26:06.06 --> 00:26:07.34
So it's 1965.

558
00:26:07.34 --> 00:26:09.54
So you're starting to hear about Vietnam.

559
00:26:09.54 --> 00:26:11.50
You guys must be talking about Vietnam.

560
00:26:11.50 --> 00:26:12.46
No, no.

561
00:26:12.46 --> 00:26:21.10
Because that happened in January of 1965.

562
00:26:21.10 --> 00:26:25.18
And summer of 64, I worked through college

563
00:26:25.18 --> 00:26:28.70
at a small summer stock playhouse

564
00:26:28.70 --> 00:26:31.50
because I was in the drama club in college.

565
00:26:31.50 --> 00:26:35.54
And you meet this guy and meet that guy and so forth.

566
00:26:35.54 --> 00:26:39.78
And all very legitimate, if you will, good people,

567
00:26:39.78 --> 00:26:42.74
not these sorts of flaky dumb people

568
00:26:42.74 --> 00:26:49.02
that you might think of when you think of theater sort of people.

569
00:26:49.02 --> 00:26:50.98
And I had a mentor by this point.

570
00:26:50.98 --> 00:26:54.78
A guy from New York was old enough to be my father.

571
00:26:54.78 --> 00:26:58.50
And he said, when you graduate, where are you going to do?

572
00:26:58.50 --> 00:27:00.74
And I said, well, I don't know.

573
00:27:00.74 --> 00:27:06.74
This paperwork and the Air Force to Fly and stuff.

574
00:27:06.74 --> 00:27:10.02
And he said, they were looking for a guy like you

575
00:27:10.02 --> 00:27:14.26
at a theater in Baltimore that I am going to, he said.

576
00:27:14.26 --> 00:27:15.98
Should I mention you to them?

577
00:27:15.98 --> 00:27:18.74
And I said, well, OK.

578
00:27:18.74 --> 00:27:21.62
So he called me in about a week or so.

579
00:27:21.62 --> 00:27:24.66
And he said, they want 15 minutes of drama

580
00:27:24.66 --> 00:27:28.94
and 15 minutes of comedy if you can do that.

581
00:27:28.94 --> 00:27:31.02
They want to talk to you.

582
00:27:31.02 --> 00:27:36.22
So I went to a woman in the summer stock company, Grace

583
00:27:36.22 --> 00:27:37.78
Chapman, wonderful woman.

584
00:27:37.78 --> 00:27:39.10
And I said, can you help me?

585
00:27:39.10 --> 00:27:40.10
And she did.

586
00:27:40.10 --> 00:27:41.54
I said, I want to do it like this.

587
00:27:41.54 --> 00:27:42.54
And she said, no, no, no.

588
00:27:42.54 --> 00:27:46.26
We're going to do it this way and so forth.

589
00:27:46.26 --> 00:27:48.98
So rehearsed it with her.

590
00:27:48.98 --> 00:27:51.42
Have to memorize everything, of course.

591
00:27:51.42 --> 00:27:56.70
Did all that and went down to Baltimore, stood up on the stage.

592
00:27:56.70 --> 00:27:58.06
Lights.

593
00:27:58.06 --> 00:27:58.98
And they've got what?

594
00:27:58.98 --> 00:28:01.50
A few people are watching you to judge you?

595
00:28:01.50 --> 00:28:03.46
The two bosses sitting in the city.

596
00:28:03.46 --> 00:28:06.22
And they're thinking of giving you some kind of a role?

597
00:28:06.22 --> 00:28:09.90
No, they had a program there where you actually

598
00:28:09.90 --> 00:28:16.02
worked as a, in the union deal, the actors union.

599
00:28:16.02 --> 00:28:17.98
It's called Actors Equity.

600
00:28:17.98 --> 00:28:21.66
You work as a local jobber and it's called.

601
00:28:21.66 --> 00:28:22.86
Doing what?

602
00:28:22.86 --> 00:28:23.70
What's your job?

603
00:28:23.70 --> 00:28:26.58
Well, they've got you.

604
00:28:26.58 --> 00:28:29.14
They've got you by the short hairs, as they say.

605
00:28:29.14 --> 00:28:34.10
And you will get role.

606
00:28:34.10 --> 00:28:37.74
Maybe the minor, maybe you were just a walk on for this one.

607
00:28:37.74 --> 00:28:39.58
And maybe something serious.

608
00:28:39.58 --> 00:28:42.38
I got one very nice role out of it.

609
00:28:42.38 --> 00:28:48.90
I was the elder son in Galileo by Bertolt Brecht.

610
00:28:48.90 --> 00:28:53.38
He was a notable European communist.

611
00:28:53.38 --> 00:28:59.54
But a good director there for that, John Marley, the guy who,

612
00:28:59.54 --> 00:29:07.06
a lot of people, he was a workhorse, a Hollywood movie actor.

613
00:29:07.06 --> 00:29:12.90
He was the guy in bed with a horse during the first Godfather

614
00:29:12.90 --> 00:29:13.70
film.

615
00:29:13.70 --> 00:29:16.94
That was John Marley and a nice man as well.

616
00:29:16.94 --> 00:29:18.02
Anyway.

617
00:29:18.02 --> 00:29:20.54
So wait, so this was in the summertime you were doing this?

618
00:29:20.54 --> 00:29:24.50
Summer stock in a barn, believe it or not, in Pennsylvania.

619
00:29:24.50 --> 00:29:29.34
And then Jerry Richards was a New York guy, old enough to be my dad,

620
00:29:29.34 --> 00:29:34.70
said he was going to this equity company in Baltimore,

621
00:29:34.70 --> 00:29:37.14
relatively new, called Center Stage.

622
00:29:37.14 --> 00:29:39.26
It's still active today.

623
00:29:39.26 --> 00:29:42.46
And was I interested, did you have another thing in mind?

624
00:29:42.46 --> 00:29:44.98
And I went back and I said to my mother,

625
00:29:44.98 --> 00:29:47.02
been passing, I was thinking about this.

626
00:29:47.02 --> 00:29:50.18
She said, do what you have to do, all right?

627
00:29:50.18 --> 00:29:54.74
So I hitchhiked once again.

628
00:29:54.74 --> 00:29:55.58
To Baltimore.

629
00:29:55.58 --> 00:29:56.10
To Baltimore.

630
00:29:56.10 --> 00:29:58.34
And how long did you stay in Baltimore for?

631
00:29:58.34 --> 00:30:04.30
Only until I got a big fat envelope in the mail from DoD.

632
00:30:04.30 --> 00:30:08.22
And it said, we will teach you to fly if you want to.

633
00:30:08.22 --> 00:30:10.22
And of course, the draft was there.

634
00:30:10.22 --> 00:30:13.46
And I had already called the draft board and I said,

635
00:30:13.46 --> 00:30:14.50
where am I?

636
00:30:14.50 --> 00:30:17.54
And they said, we can't tell you by the law.

637
00:30:17.54 --> 00:30:21.42
But I'll tell you this, you're close to the front of the drawer.

638
00:30:21.42 --> 00:30:23.46
I remember that very well.

639
00:30:23.46 --> 00:30:25.74
I thought, I've got to do something about this.

640
00:30:25.74 --> 00:30:27.42
I wonder what to do about this.

641
00:30:27.42 --> 00:30:31.98
And I went to a fellow guy who was in the same position

642
00:30:31.98 --> 00:30:33.74
I was in the company.

643
00:30:33.74 --> 00:30:35.70
And I said, I don't know what to do.

644
00:30:35.70 --> 00:30:37.34
And he said, do what I did.

645
00:30:37.34 --> 00:30:41.50
Tell them you like boys, not girls.

646
00:30:41.50 --> 00:30:43.94
I said, that's not true.

647
00:30:43.94 --> 00:30:45.62
He said, it's not true with me either.

648
00:30:45.62 --> 00:30:46.50
But it got me right.

649
00:30:46.50 --> 00:30:48.70
They could go sit on the bench over there.

650
00:30:48.70 --> 00:30:52.10
And they asked, do you really like boys rather than girls?

651
00:30:52.10 --> 00:30:54.78
And he said, I just said, that's right.

652
00:30:54.78 --> 00:30:55.30
I do.

653
00:30:55.30 --> 00:30:57.18
And that was the end of that.

654
00:30:57.18 --> 00:30:57.78
And I got off.

655
00:30:57.78 --> 00:30:59.78
I said, oh, boy.

656
00:30:59.78 --> 00:31:01.82
That may be good advice some ways.

657
00:31:01.82 --> 00:31:03.78
But I thought somewhere down the road,

658
00:31:03.78 --> 00:31:07.86
somebody's going to drag that out 40 years from now.

659
00:31:07.86 --> 00:31:09.46
And so I didn't want to do that.

660
00:31:09.46 --> 00:31:11.82
And lo and behold, I get this big fat envelope in my mouth.

661
00:31:11.82 --> 00:31:15.02
I go to Jerry Richards, my mentor.

662
00:31:15.02 --> 00:31:15.86
I said, what should I do?

663
00:31:15.86 --> 00:31:20.62
He said, he was a combat veteran of World War II.

664
00:31:20.62 --> 00:31:23.46
A dog-faced soldier had funny stories

665
00:31:23.46 --> 00:31:28.30
to tell about being on a line of March, hot, sweaty,

666
00:31:28.30 --> 00:31:33.54
and an Italian farmer going by with a wooden tank

667
00:31:33.54 --> 00:31:37.86
on a little wagon pulled by a horse.

668
00:31:37.86 --> 00:31:41.14
And the second lieutenant, whoever it was,

669
00:31:41.14 --> 00:31:43.34
said, stay away from that tank.

670
00:31:43.34 --> 00:31:49.14
We all knew it was full of wine or grape juice anyway.

671
00:31:49.14 --> 00:31:52.50
And he said, we got two thirds of the line through there.

672
00:31:52.50 --> 00:31:54.62
And somebody went, boom, boom, boom.

673
00:31:54.62 --> 00:31:56.22
And that was it.

674
00:31:56.22 --> 00:31:57.78
Everything collapsed.

675
00:31:57.78 --> 00:32:00.06
Anyway, super nice guy.

676
00:32:00.06 --> 00:32:01.94
And I went to Jerry.

677
00:32:01.94 --> 00:32:03.62
And I said, what should I do about this?

678
00:32:03.62 --> 00:32:06.38
And he said, well, you always come back to this,

679
00:32:06.38 --> 00:32:08.66
but you're never getting another chance to do that.

680
00:32:08.66 --> 00:32:11.42
So I signed on the dotted line.

681
00:32:11.42 --> 00:32:18.42
And I went into the Air Force on the 2nd of January, 1975.

682
00:32:18.42 --> 00:32:19.50
1965.

683
00:32:19.50 --> 00:32:21.34
65.

684
00:32:21.34 --> 00:32:22.34
Yeah, 65.

685
00:32:22.34 --> 00:32:23.06
He said, 75.

686
00:32:23.06 --> 00:32:24.06
That's right.

687
00:32:24.06 --> 00:32:24.62
65.

688
00:32:24.62 --> 00:32:26.98
So yeah, so that early part of Vietnam.

689
00:32:26.98 --> 00:32:30.06
Because I always think in a way the news kind of worked.

690
00:32:30.06 --> 00:32:33.14
It was the battle of the I-Dreng Valley in 1965

691
00:32:33.14 --> 00:32:34.90
where it really hit the news.

692
00:32:34.90 --> 00:32:36.10
And there was casualties.

693
00:32:36.10 --> 00:32:40.78
And it seemed like the escalation really kind of started.

694
00:32:40.78 --> 00:32:45.02
So you get done with the Officer Candidate School.

695
00:32:45.02 --> 00:32:47.70
And then you get your slot to flight school?

696
00:32:47.70 --> 00:32:48.34
Right.

697
00:32:48.34 --> 00:32:52.90
And that was at Webb Air Force Base in West Texas,

698
00:32:52.90 --> 00:32:56.46
at Big Spring, Texas.

699
00:32:56.46 --> 00:33:01.18
Pretty much of a barren place, just east of the big, big oil

700
00:33:01.18 --> 00:33:02.14
fields.

701
00:33:02.14 --> 00:33:05.18
But there were plenty of oil wells around where I was,

702
00:33:05.18 --> 00:33:06.46
around Big Spring.

703
00:33:06.46 --> 00:33:13.90
But the big oil fields around Midland and Odessa, Texas.

704
00:33:13.90 --> 00:33:17.02
Permium Basin, it's called.

705
00:33:17.02 --> 00:33:22.46
And there had been at least one crash at Big Spring, Texas.

706
00:33:22.46 --> 00:33:24.74
They made a very big deal out of it, and rightly so.

707
00:33:24.74 --> 00:33:28.82
The guy was confused about stars and oil fields.

708
00:33:28.82 --> 00:33:32.22
Every drilling, not their drilling rig,

709
00:33:32.22 --> 00:33:36.34
but every pumping deal has its own light bulb on it.

710
00:33:36.34 --> 00:33:38.46
And he got confused and rolled over.

711
00:33:38.46 --> 00:33:39.74
To your shame.

712
00:33:39.74 --> 00:33:41.90
Yeah, so really ashamed.

713
00:33:41.90 --> 00:33:45.46
But I learned to fly there and then went to the.

714
00:33:45.46 --> 00:33:46.34
How was flight school?

715
00:33:49.50 --> 00:33:53.94
It was tough for me at first because I didn't know a wing

716
00:33:53.94 --> 00:33:58.54
from a tail, an aileron from an elevator, anything.

717
00:33:58.54 --> 00:34:02.10
And about half those guys had private licenses.

718
00:34:02.10 --> 00:34:06.06
At least half of them had private licenses.

719
00:34:06.06 --> 00:34:10.46
And a couple of them had commercial multi-engines.

720
00:34:10.46 --> 00:34:13.14
They weren't just walking through the thing.

721
00:34:13.14 --> 00:34:15.78
But I was slow to get going.

722
00:34:15.78 --> 00:34:19.62
But when I got into the second half, which was the T-38

723
00:34:19.62 --> 00:34:22.74
at that time, I did very well.

724
00:34:22.74 --> 00:34:29.02
But it's like a baseball player trying to bring his average

725
00:34:29.02 --> 00:34:31.98
up the second half of the season.

726
00:34:31.98 --> 00:34:35.98
So your grade point average was a problem for me.

727
00:34:35.98 --> 00:34:41.22
And I wound up getting a B-52 assignment.

728
00:34:41.22 --> 00:34:45.26
My roommates got C-130s, which was a very desirable deal.

729
00:34:45.26 --> 00:34:46.94
If you didn't want to get shot at,

730
00:34:46.94 --> 00:34:50.18
it turned out to be very foolish.

731
00:34:50.18 --> 00:34:55.54
Because in C-130, you got shot at in the Vietnam War.

732
00:34:55.54 --> 00:35:02.38
And one of my roommates got Air Defense Command F-104,

733
00:35:02.38 --> 00:35:05.70
which was considered to be creme de la creme,

734
00:35:05.70 --> 00:35:10.06
until I got assigned to the F-4.

735
00:35:10.06 --> 00:35:12.22
But first, you had to do your B-52 time.

736
00:35:12.22 --> 00:35:12.72
Right.

737
00:35:12.72 --> 00:35:15.86
The G-Model in Rome, New York, wonderful place,

738
00:35:15.86 --> 00:35:17.26
wonderful people there.

739
00:35:17.26 --> 00:35:20.82
I liked everything about it except sitting alert.

740
00:35:20.82 --> 00:35:21.98
Awful.

741
00:35:21.98 --> 00:35:25.70
So this is now what, 1966 or so?

742
00:35:25.70 --> 00:35:26.90
Yeah, that's right.

743
00:35:26.90 --> 00:35:31.90
And you're assigned to the B-52 squadron in Rome, New York.

744
00:35:31.90 --> 00:35:32.98
Yeah.

745
00:35:32.98 --> 00:35:35.98
Very heavily decorated squadron from World War II.

746
00:35:35.98 --> 00:35:40.18
I can't remember the number, 488 or something like that.

747
00:35:40.18 --> 00:35:43.22
Eighth Air Force.

748
00:35:43.22 --> 00:35:49.98
I had the first guy they put me with was a guy of shorter stature.

749
00:35:49.98 --> 00:35:52.02
And I think he had a problem about that.

750
00:35:52.02 --> 00:35:54.14
And I was six feet tall and whatnot.

751
00:35:54.14 --> 00:35:58.66
And all the way down to him saying, I said, that's not so.

752
00:35:58.66 --> 00:35:59.62
He said, it is so.

753
00:35:59.62 --> 00:36:01.34
And you shut up because I'm a major.

754
00:36:01.34 --> 00:36:04.50
And you're just a goddamn first lieutenant.

755
00:36:04.50 --> 00:36:06.58
Whoa, OK.

756
00:36:06.58 --> 00:36:09.94
But at any rate, he fired me, so to speak, basically.

757
00:36:09.94 --> 00:36:12.06
He didn't want to fly with me anymore

758
00:36:12.06 --> 00:36:16.30
because I may have made better landings than he did.

759
00:36:16.30 --> 00:36:18.58
Because the next guy I got was a family man.

760
00:36:18.58 --> 00:36:20.70
And we got along like brothers.

761
00:36:20.70 --> 00:36:21.62
And it was great.

762
00:36:21.62 --> 00:36:24.34
So the one lead pilot or whatever it was called,

763
00:36:24.34 --> 00:36:25.98
the lead pilot, the major?

764
00:36:25.98 --> 00:36:26.90
Yeah.

765
00:36:26.90 --> 00:36:28.70
He didn't like flying with you.

766
00:36:28.70 --> 00:36:29.22
Right.

767
00:36:29.22 --> 00:36:30.74
Well, he didn't like your attitude or something.

768
00:36:30.74 --> 00:36:32.38
And he didn't like my attitude either.

769
00:36:32.38 --> 00:36:33.58
So he got rid of you.

770
00:36:33.58 --> 00:36:33.90
Right.

771
00:36:33.90 --> 00:36:35.34
But then you just moved to another guy?

772
00:36:35.34 --> 00:36:35.82
Yeah.

773
00:36:35.82 --> 00:36:38.18
Well, they gave me another guy.

774
00:36:38.18 --> 00:36:39.58
You don't have any choice about it.

775
00:36:39.58 --> 00:36:42.06
But we got along.

776
00:36:42.06 --> 00:36:43.86
Had fun every day.

777
00:36:43.86 --> 00:36:46.66
And what's the deal with sitting alert?

778
00:36:46.66 --> 00:36:51.78
Well, they did it two different ways.

779
00:36:51.78 --> 00:36:55.42
At Romney Arc, where I was, they had eight airplanes

780
00:36:55.42 --> 00:36:58.66
on alert at any one time.

781
00:36:58.66 --> 00:37:03.66
All the airplanes that I was on had two Hound dogs stand off

782
00:37:03.66 --> 00:37:08.26
missiles with thermonuclear weapons in them.

783
00:37:08.26 --> 00:37:10.82
The Mark 28 at that time.

784
00:37:10.82 --> 00:37:13.74
I don't think it's classified anymore.

785
00:37:13.74 --> 00:37:20.38
But the highest yield on those, single warhead per.

786
00:37:20.38 --> 00:37:24.74
And there was a pop on there.

787
00:37:24.74 --> 00:37:28.98
And then four thermonuclear weapons in the Bombay.

788
00:37:28.98 --> 00:37:34.42
And then four Quail decoy missiles in the Bombay.

789
00:37:34.42 --> 00:37:41.06
And the targets for the ones I was on, well, I was on a

790
00:37:41.06 --> 00:37:45.02
mission that was downtown Moscow, believe it or not, and

791
00:37:45.02 --> 00:37:46.66
land in Turkey.

792
00:37:46.66 --> 00:37:49.50
I think all of the ones I was on were land in Turkey.

793
00:37:49.50 --> 00:37:50.94
Because you were out of fuel.

794
00:37:50.94 --> 00:37:54.94
By then you were fueled south of Iceland.

795
00:37:54.94 --> 00:38:01.14
And then went in and then turned straight south and landed

796
00:38:01.14 --> 00:38:06.82
on an abandoned airfield in central Turkey.

797
00:38:06.82 --> 00:38:11.42
And you were instructed to get fuel by Jerry Can.

798
00:38:11.42 --> 00:38:12.54
This is silly.

799
00:38:12.54 --> 00:38:13.30
And we knew it.

800
00:38:16.58 --> 00:38:18.06
Jerry Can was not enough.

801
00:38:18.06 --> 00:38:21.78
He had eight J57s and a B52.

802
00:38:21.78 --> 00:38:27.90
And H model had modified J57s that were fan jet engines.

803
00:38:27.90 --> 00:38:28.78
But it was silly.

804
00:38:28.78 --> 00:38:33.62
You'd never forget enough fuel to refuel the thing, to fly

805
00:38:33.62 --> 00:38:34.50
it anywhere.

806
00:38:34.50 --> 00:38:37.74
So I mean, was that just because once you flew over Moscow

807
00:38:37.74 --> 00:38:40.34
and dropped nuclear weapons, it wouldn't really matter where

808
00:38:40.34 --> 00:38:40.74
you were getting?

809
00:38:40.74 --> 00:38:41.46
What was the?

810
00:38:41.46 --> 00:38:41.98
Pretty much.

811
00:38:41.98 --> 00:38:45.38
Because you're assuming that the world would be a conflagration

812
00:38:45.38 --> 00:38:48.38
and would be pretty much of a mess.

813
00:38:48.38 --> 00:38:52.30
But at that point, you would truly a thermonuclear war

814
00:38:52.30 --> 00:38:56.90
would have finished by that time, I guess.

815
00:38:56.90 --> 00:39:00.50
And everything would be an awful, awful mess.

816
00:39:00.50 --> 00:39:05.22
And are you sitting, like are the weapons loaded on the aircraft?

817
00:39:05.22 --> 00:39:05.94
Just sit there, stage?

818
00:39:05.94 --> 00:39:06.70
Absolutely.

819
00:39:06.70 --> 00:39:10.26
Positively with an armed guard on every airplane.

820
00:39:10.26 --> 00:39:14.14
Walking around underneath every airplane 24 hours a day.

821
00:39:14.14 --> 00:39:18.06
Was there any events that would heighten your readiness?

822
00:39:18.06 --> 00:39:28.42
They would have practice alerts that could happen at any time.

823
00:39:28.42 --> 00:39:32.82
SAC, World Strategic Air Command, worldwide,

824
00:39:32.82 --> 00:39:34.18
would call an alert.

825
00:39:34.18 --> 00:39:39.22
And every SAC base on the planet, even in obscure places,

826
00:39:39.22 --> 00:39:44.54
would do what they were told to do.

827
00:39:44.54 --> 00:39:48.06
And they basically had three commands.

828
00:39:48.06 --> 00:39:53.18
One, to man the airplanes and start them at stay in place.

829
00:39:53.18 --> 00:39:58.46
Second, start the airplanes and taxi down the runway,

830
00:39:58.46 --> 00:40:02.66
just motivate the flying machines.

831
00:40:02.66 --> 00:40:04.78
And third would be a real launch.

832
00:40:04.78 --> 00:40:06.70
Actually, there were two kinds of launches,

833
00:40:06.70 --> 00:40:13.10
launch to a holding point short of total commitment.

834
00:40:13.10 --> 00:40:18.02
Or four, total commitment from minute one.

835
00:40:18.02 --> 00:40:23.66
So obviously, the third and fourth never happened with me.

836
00:40:27.54 --> 00:40:31.58
The alert was at Rome New York, at Griffiths Air Force Base

837
00:40:31.58 --> 00:40:32.82
of Orange, is where I was.

838
00:40:32.82 --> 00:40:36.90
And wonderful people there, too, was seven days.

839
00:40:36.90 --> 00:40:38.30
You had seven days on.

840
00:40:38.30 --> 00:40:41.54
And the rules were half your time on alert.

841
00:40:41.54 --> 00:40:43.90
You had three.

842
00:40:43.90 --> 00:40:46.14
But it didn't really work out that way,

843
00:40:46.14 --> 00:40:51.26
because you didn't get away from the base until, in this case,

844
00:40:51.26 --> 00:40:55.06
Thursday, 12 o'clock or something like that.

845
00:40:55.06 --> 00:40:57.98
And you lost half the day.

846
00:40:57.98 --> 00:41:03.50
And then they would schedule you for a flight, maybe,

847
00:41:03.50 --> 00:41:07.78
Monday night at 8 PM.

848
00:41:07.78 --> 00:41:11.70
So Monday was sort of gone, because you had to sleep,

849
00:41:11.70 --> 00:41:14.58
because you were going to fly for 12 hours.

850
00:41:14.58 --> 00:41:17.46
You took off at 8 PM, you were going to land at 8 o'clock

851
00:41:17.46 --> 00:41:18.78
Tuesday morning.

852
00:41:18.78 --> 00:41:23.50
All those missions, those training missions, were eight hours.

853
00:41:23.50 --> 00:41:27.54
But training missions were sort of fun and interesting.

854
00:41:27.54 --> 00:41:29.54
I spent a lot of time with my hands in my lap.

855
00:41:29.54 --> 00:41:33.06
But nevertheless, they were interesting.

856
00:41:33.06 --> 00:41:35.30
And you went all over the United States,

857
00:41:35.30 --> 00:41:38.98
all over the United States doing those things.

858
00:41:38.98 --> 00:41:40.90
And a lot of them were at low level,

859
00:41:40.90 --> 00:41:44.86
because that's what you would do in the case of a nuclear war.

860
00:41:44.86 --> 00:41:46.66
Oh, it's a low-level attack?

861
00:41:46.66 --> 00:41:47.90
Oh, yes.

862
00:41:47.90 --> 00:41:54.22
The B-52s were all assigned a low altitude.

863
00:41:54.22 --> 00:41:55.22
Like how low?

864
00:41:55.22 --> 00:41:57.30
200 feet.

865
00:41:57.30 --> 00:41:59.10
That's good, underneath radar?

866
00:41:59.10 --> 00:42:00.18
Right.

867
00:42:00.18 --> 00:42:01.14
Yeah.

868
00:42:01.14 --> 00:42:04.26
As low as you want to go is what I was told.

869
00:42:04.26 --> 00:42:07.14
I said, this is a poker deck route,

870
00:42:07.14 --> 00:42:09.58
and it's published at 400 feet.

871
00:42:09.58 --> 00:42:14.66
How low are we talking about here if we actually do have a war?

872
00:42:14.66 --> 00:42:17.02
As low as you want to go.

873
00:42:17.02 --> 00:42:22.82
I said, one point, you have charts that were accurate,

874
00:42:22.82 --> 00:42:26.34
accurate, and classified, obviously.

875
00:42:26.34 --> 00:42:31.46
But I said to one of the guys who worked in the vault,

876
00:42:31.46 --> 00:42:34.46
you had to target study while you were on alert.

877
00:42:34.46 --> 00:42:38.14
And I said, you show telephone poles here.

878
00:42:38.14 --> 00:42:43.14
Here I am to co-pilot, looking for the next turn.

879
00:42:43.14 --> 00:42:45.66
Can I count those telephone poles?

880
00:42:45.66 --> 00:42:46.94
Yes, you can.

881
00:42:46.94 --> 00:42:50.42
Whoa, they were all done by U2 or by satellite.

882
00:42:50.42 --> 00:42:54.74
I think the satellites were just starting at that time.

883
00:42:54.74 --> 00:42:59.46
So I said, so it would be the 28th telephone pole.

884
00:42:59.46 --> 00:43:03.06
I can turn left to 030.

885
00:43:03.06 --> 00:43:04.46
Yep.

886
00:43:04.46 --> 00:43:08.10
Anyway, so what was the question?

887
00:43:08.10 --> 00:43:09.34
Where would the heck we're going?

888
00:43:09.34 --> 00:43:12.10
Well, it's very interesting to hear

889
00:43:12.10 --> 00:43:16.78
sort of what your status was as a pilot.

890
00:43:16.78 --> 00:43:19.74
And I actually asked you what level of alert, what's

891
00:43:19.74 --> 00:43:21.38
the highest level of alert you are?

892
00:43:21.38 --> 00:43:23.82
Because obviously, you missed the Cuban missile crisis.

893
00:43:23.82 --> 00:43:24.22
That's right.

894
00:43:24.22 --> 00:43:27.34
Because I'm sure that would have been a very high alert.

895
00:43:27.34 --> 00:43:28.34
Right.

896
00:43:28.34 --> 00:43:29.86
Do you think they got airborne for that?

897
00:43:29.86 --> 00:43:30.94
I don't think so.

898
00:43:30.94 --> 00:43:31.94
I don't think so.

899
00:43:31.94 --> 00:43:34.98
I don't remember ever asking anybody.

900
00:43:34.98 --> 00:43:37.34
But I don't think that that happened.

901
00:43:37.34 --> 00:43:37.94
No.

902
00:43:37.94 --> 00:43:43.02
And that had to be a little bit of a strange weight

903
00:43:43.02 --> 00:43:46.22
on your shoulders to think about, especially

904
00:43:46.22 --> 00:43:48.66
with your background, with your English teacher that

905
00:43:48.66 --> 00:43:51.86
didn't like the atomic bombs dropped on Japan.

906
00:43:51.86 --> 00:43:52.36
Right.

907
00:43:52.36 --> 00:43:54.30
And here you are with a mission tasking

908
00:43:54.30 --> 00:43:56.66
that if you get this mission, you're

909
00:43:56.66 --> 00:44:01.14
going to fly and annihilate basically the world.

910
00:44:01.14 --> 00:44:03.86
Well, I have a little bit of a funny story about it.

911
00:44:03.86 --> 00:44:05.34
Let's hear about that.

912
00:44:05.34 --> 00:44:06.50
Turns into a funny story.

913
00:44:06.50 --> 00:44:07.14
I like that.

914
00:44:07.14 --> 00:44:10.42
In the G and the H, we had the gunner up front.

915
00:44:10.42 --> 00:44:12.30
And the guns that were in the tail.

916
00:44:12.30 --> 00:44:15.30
So these are the G and H models of the B-52.

917
00:44:15.30 --> 00:44:16.14
Right.

918
00:44:16.14 --> 00:44:18.54
Up to that, the gunner rode in the tail.

919
00:44:18.54 --> 00:44:21.30
And if he were to bail out, he would

920
00:44:21.30 --> 00:44:25.34
jettison his turret, which weighed something like 2,000

921
00:44:25.34 --> 00:44:26.38
pounds, everything.

922
00:44:26.38 --> 00:44:32.10
His ammunition and his 50 calibers and everything short

923
00:44:32.10 --> 00:44:33.42
of the seat.

924
00:44:33.42 --> 00:44:36.38
He sat on a chemical toilet back there, incidentally.

925
00:44:36.38 --> 00:44:38.42
But then he would bail out.

926
00:44:38.42 --> 00:44:41.22
He did not have an ejection seat.

927
00:44:41.22 --> 00:44:42.86
It was right in front of his toes.

928
00:44:42.86 --> 00:44:45.30
And he just stepped forward or leaned forward now

929
00:44:45.30 --> 00:44:48.58
to win with a conventional parachute.

930
00:44:48.58 --> 00:44:54.98
Anyway, the gunner and the G and the H models up front.

931
00:44:54.98 --> 00:44:58.98
And the cockpit arrangement is different in the G and the H

932
00:44:58.98 --> 00:45:04.06
than it was in the earlier, up to the F model, B-52.

933
00:45:04.06 --> 00:45:05.70
The G's no longer exist.

934
00:45:05.70 --> 00:45:10.86
They went with the strategic arms limitation treaty.

935
00:45:10.86 --> 00:45:14.06
And the G's got their pictures of them getting their wings

936
00:45:14.06 --> 00:45:18.70
cut off that they took airborne pictures of all that.

937
00:45:18.70 --> 00:45:21.86
So comply with the Russians.

938
00:45:21.86 --> 00:45:22.42
The Soviets?

939
00:45:22.42 --> 00:45:23.74
Yeah.

940
00:45:23.74 --> 00:45:24.58
But at any rate.

941
00:45:24.58 --> 00:45:26.86
The G and the H internally are the same.

942
00:45:26.86 --> 00:45:33.34
And the ECM officer and the gunner ride facing backwards.

943
00:45:33.34 --> 00:45:37.30
And now it was going to.

944
00:45:37.30 --> 00:45:37.98
Oh, yeah.

945
00:45:37.98 --> 00:45:43.18
So on your charts, when you do your first day of alert target

946
00:45:43.18 --> 00:45:47.06
study, it's the same charts every time.

947
00:45:47.06 --> 00:45:49.66
The gunners, you sit across the table.

948
00:45:49.66 --> 00:45:55.02
And I said, oh, you have LPBN.

949
00:45:55.02 --> 00:45:56.14
That means something.

950
00:45:56.14 --> 00:46:03.74
And E35, that means something across the route of flight.

951
00:46:03.74 --> 00:46:06.58
And I said, LPBO.

952
00:46:06.58 --> 00:46:12.02
In the same lettering, stencil, same ink, same everything.

953
00:46:12.02 --> 00:46:14.62
I said, what's LPBO?

954
00:46:14.62 --> 00:46:18.86
He said, last point of bailout.

955
00:46:18.86 --> 00:46:20.34
That's over Finland.

956
00:46:20.34 --> 00:46:21.54
He said, exactly right.

957
00:46:21.54 --> 00:46:23.34
I'm not going to anybody's nuclear war.

958
00:46:23.34 --> 00:46:24.50
I'm leaving.

959
00:46:24.50 --> 00:46:25.86
I'm over Finland.

960
00:46:25.86 --> 00:46:29.06
I'm taking the seat pack with me with the.22 rifle,

961
00:46:29.06 --> 00:46:31.10
the sleeping bag, and everything.

962
00:46:31.10 --> 00:46:34.38
I'm out of here.

963
00:46:34.38 --> 00:46:36.94
But it never happened.

964
00:46:36.94 --> 00:46:40.66
He was an E6 enlisted guy.

965
00:46:40.66 --> 00:46:42.82
And nice family man and everything else.

966
00:46:42.82 --> 00:46:44.30
But he said, I'm not going to nuclear war.

967
00:46:44.30 --> 00:46:46.14
You're nuts.

968
00:46:46.14 --> 00:46:48.50
So how long did you do this job for?

969
00:46:48.50 --> 00:46:49.18
A year.

970
00:46:49.18 --> 00:46:55.30
Well, including the RAG, if you will, in Merced, California,

971
00:46:55.30 --> 00:46:56.90
a year and a half.

972
00:46:56.90 --> 00:47:00.90
But then I got the big fat envelope that said,

973
00:47:00.90 --> 00:47:03.02
here is your interservice transfer.

974
00:47:03.02 --> 00:47:05.22
If you want to do this, you can do this.

975
00:47:05.22 --> 00:47:06.82
And that's what you had applied for?

976
00:47:06.82 --> 00:47:07.14
Right.

977
00:47:07.14 --> 00:47:10.22
And why did you try and do an interservice transfer

978
00:47:10.22 --> 00:47:11.46
to the Navy?

979
00:47:11.46 --> 00:47:13.98
Because I didn't want two sides to that.

980
00:47:13.98 --> 00:47:17.10
And there's popping your peas again there.

981
00:47:17.10 --> 00:47:20.82
I didn't want to sit alert anymore.

982
00:47:20.82 --> 00:47:26.30
I didn't like riding around with my hands in my lap.

983
00:47:26.30 --> 00:47:31.74
And going way back, I had this idea in the back of my head.

984
00:47:31.74 --> 00:47:36.46
My first cross country in the T-37 out of Web Air Force Base,

985
00:47:36.46 --> 00:47:39.58
we stopped somewhere I can't remember.

986
00:47:39.58 --> 00:47:43.66
And there were two Navy guys there wearing golf shirts

987
00:47:43.66 --> 00:47:47.58
underneath their flight suits.

988
00:47:47.58 --> 00:47:51.42
And through the open door, there were two A4s parked out there.

989
00:47:51.42 --> 00:47:56.06
And they said something like USS Independence or USS,

990
00:47:56.06 --> 00:47:58.42
who knows, Forest Hall or who knows what.

991
00:47:58.42 --> 00:48:01.78
I thought, isn't that hot stuff?

992
00:48:01.78 --> 00:48:05.70
These guys can go to sea with those things and go,

993
00:48:05.70 --> 00:48:08.46
I don't know, anywhere they want.

994
00:48:08.46 --> 00:48:09.82
That's hot.

995
00:48:09.82 --> 00:48:15.46
And then I saw the back of a proceedings magazine.

996
00:48:15.46 --> 00:48:17.94
Proceedings used to be magazine size.

997
00:48:17.94 --> 00:48:21.58
Then it became smaller format.

998
00:48:21.58 --> 00:48:26.06
But it showed an A4 looking over the A4's shoulder,

999
00:48:26.06 --> 00:48:27.98
like the wingman or something like that.

1000
00:48:27.98 --> 00:48:28.54
Looking over it.

1001
00:48:28.54 --> 00:48:30.78
And he's on short final for our carrier.

1002
00:48:30.78 --> 00:48:34.22
And I thought, that's hot shit.

1003
00:48:34.22 --> 00:48:35.42
So that did it.

1004
00:48:35.42 --> 00:48:38.38
And was it hard to put in that interservice transfer?

1005
00:48:38.38 --> 00:48:39.98
It was pretty straightforward.

1006
00:48:39.98 --> 00:48:41.46
Well, they bounced it back at me.

1007
00:48:41.46 --> 00:48:43.70
So no, the carrier format's wrong.

1008
00:48:43.70 --> 00:48:45.26
It has to be this way and that way.

1009
00:48:45.26 --> 00:48:46.14
I have to do that.

1010
00:48:46.14 --> 00:48:48.02
And I said, fine.

1011
00:48:48.02 --> 00:48:49.34
Well, what do you want us to do?

1012
00:48:49.34 --> 00:48:51.78
I said, well, you tell me it's wrong.

1013
00:48:51.78 --> 00:48:56.50
I did it according to what was in the Publications Library.

1014
00:48:56.50 --> 00:48:57.94
You do it.

1015
00:48:57.94 --> 00:48:59.38
I said, well, I guess we have to.

1016
00:48:59.38 --> 00:49:01.06
And they did.

1017
00:49:01.06 --> 00:49:04.50
Then I signed everything the second time and then the way it went.

1018
00:49:04.50 --> 00:49:07.86
And you got straight into the pilot pipeline?

1019
00:49:07.86 --> 00:49:12.74
Well, no, I was, you know, when you're a military officer,

1020
00:49:12.74 --> 00:49:15.94
you are an officer of the United States.

1021
00:49:15.94 --> 00:49:19.26
You're not an Air Force officer or a Navy officer

1022
00:49:19.26 --> 00:49:24.74
or even an officer of the, there's a land survey

1023
00:49:24.74 --> 00:49:27.30
and mapping service.

1024
00:49:27.30 --> 00:49:29.62
They have military uniforms.

1025
00:49:29.62 --> 00:49:33.70
You are an officer of the United States.

1026
00:49:33.70 --> 00:49:37.74
So it isn't like you change services.

1027
00:49:37.74 --> 00:49:40.54
You change uniforms and you change terminology

1028
00:49:40.54 --> 00:49:43.66
and you change verbiage.

1029
00:49:43.66 --> 00:49:49.02
And the name of your grade changes from first lieutenant

1030
00:49:49.02 --> 00:49:50.38
to lieutenant junior grade.

1031
00:49:50.38 --> 00:49:55.14
But they can put you anywhere they want.

1032
00:49:55.14 --> 00:49:58.46
You can be a seal who's a lieutenant commander

1033
00:49:58.46 --> 00:50:00.18
and they can say, guess what?

1034
00:50:00.18 --> 00:50:04.18
We want you in the embassy in Tunisia

1035
00:50:04.18 --> 00:50:06.42
and it's only going to be six months.

1036
00:50:06.42 --> 00:50:08.58
But you'll be wearing civilian clothes

1037
00:50:08.58 --> 00:50:11.38
and you'll be responsible for us and so on, us and so on.

1038
00:50:11.38 --> 00:50:12.58
And that can do that.

1039
00:50:12.58 --> 00:50:15.74
Because remember, you're appointed by the President

1040
00:50:15.74 --> 00:50:18.06
of the United States.

1041
00:50:18.06 --> 00:50:21.54
You're going to serve in that capacity.

1042
00:50:21.54 --> 00:50:23.86
So that's what happens with an inner service transfer.

1043
00:50:23.86 --> 00:50:28.14
And I was told that when you make the transfer,

1044
00:50:28.14 --> 00:50:36.38
it's basically a long table meeting of senior service

1045
00:50:36.38 --> 00:50:40.14
and I have a doc who wants to come over to the Air Force

1046
00:50:40.14 --> 00:50:45.54
and you have a junior lieutenant who wants to go Navy.

1047
00:50:45.54 --> 00:50:47.02
I'll swap you for those two.

1048
00:50:47.02 --> 00:50:47.94
OK, that's fine.

1049
00:50:47.94 --> 00:50:50.30
Let me do that and so forth and so forth.

1050
00:50:50.30 --> 00:50:51.34
And that's the way it's done.

1051
00:50:51.34 --> 00:50:53.62
But every six months or something like that

1052
00:50:53.62 --> 00:50:55.26
and it probably goes on right now.

1053
00:50:55.26 --> 00:50:56.30
I don't know.

1054
00:50:56.30 --> 00:51:00.30
But you ended up with the pilot slot somehow.

1055
00:51:00.30 --> 00:51:05.58
Yeah, well, I had orders to King's, Corpus Christi.

1056
00:51:05.58 --> 00:51:09.62
And I'm standing in a guy's office, nice guy,

1057
00:51:09.62 --> 00:51:13.50
with the Lieutenant Commander,

1058
00:51:13.50 --> 00:51:15.74
a few of the parking ramp with S-2's,

1059
00:51:15.74 --> 00:51:19.02
Stu's parked behind him, pissed an engine,

1060
00:51:19.02 --> 00:51:20.94
had a submarine airplanes.

1061
00:51:20.94 --> 00:51:23.54
It's a training facility for them.

1062
00:51:23.54 --> 00:51:26.10
And a couple of Lieutenant Commander standing over here

1063
00:51:26.10 --> 00:51:30.14
and me standing right here in front of his desk.

1064
00:51:30.14 --> 00:51:31.78
And he said, what are we going to do with you?

1065
00:51:31.78 --> 00:51:33.34
I said, I don't know.

1066
00:51:33.34 --> 00:51:35.02
I just have these orders.

1067
00:51:35.02 --> 00:51:36.74
He said, you flew jets?

1068
00:51:36.74 --> 00:51:38.34
I said, yeah?

1069
00:51:38.34 --> 00:51:40.74
He said, well, then we'll send you to Kingsville.

1070
00:51:40.74 --> 00:51:42.30
What should we do with him?

1071
00:51:42.30 --> 00:51:44.98
What happens if he can't get aboard?

1072
00:51:44.98 --> 00:51:48.66
I thought, I will get aboard.

1073
00:51:48.66 --> 00:51:50.78
So what's Kingsville?

1074
00:51:50.78 --> 00:51:53.34
Kingsville are two advanced training bases.

1075
00:51:53.34 --> 00:51:55.86
I think there is B-ville still active?

1076
00:51:55.86 --> 00:51:57.18
B-ville's close to Kingsville.

1077
00:51:57.18 --> 00:51:59.62
Yeah, and Kingsville is bigger than ever.

1078
00:51:59.62 --> 00:52:01.14
And Navy advanced.

1079
00:52:01.14 --> 00:52:04.26
At that time, there were F-9s there.

1080
00:52:04.26 --> 00:52:07.30
And I went over to Kingsville and introduced myself

1081
00:52:07.30 --> 00:52:09.66
and dropped my orders on the table, and so to speak.

1082
00:52:09.66 --> 00:52:11.10
And all very nice.

1083
00:52:11.10 --> 00:52:13.22
And looked out the window, and they

1084
00:52:13.22 --> 00:52:18.02
had these ancient airplanes, F-9s, Creme War vintage.

1085
00:52:18.02 --> 00:52:20.50
Oh, boy.

1086
00:52:20.50 --> 00:52:24.82
What ancient equipment here.

1087
00:52:24.82 --> 00:52:27.74
There was more fun to fly than you can imagine.

1088
00:52:27.74 --> 00:52:30.62
You put the power up all the way and leave it there.

1089
00:52:30.62 --> 00:52:35.18
And it was like your brother's MG with a little four-cylinder

1090
00:52:35.18 --> 00:52:38.98
engine in it was so much fun to drive, underpowered.

1091
00:52:38.98 --> 00:52:39.78
Same way.

1092
00:52:39.78 --> 00:52:41.90
Fun, fun, fun to fly.

1093
00:52:41.90 --> 00:52:49.46
It was truly a flying airplane with a wing, airfoil wing,

1094
00:52:49.46 --> 00:52:50.18
and everything else.

1095
00:52:50.18 --> 00:52:52.98
You fly, get into the phantom, and you find, no,

1096
00:52:52.98 --> 00:52:54.50
this is a machine.

1097
00:52:54.50 --> 00:52:57.14
Now, at this point, you're hearing about Vietnam.

1098
00:52:57.14 --> 00:53:00.02
Vietnam's now is 19, what, 1967?

1099
00:53:00.02 --> 00:53:00.90
Yeah.

1100
00:53:00.90 --> 00:53:03.26
So now you know what?

1101
00:53:03.26 --> 00:53:04.10
You're in a pipeline.

1102
00:53:04.10 --> 00:53:05.70
Your goal is to be a fighter pilot.

1103
00:53:05.70 --> 00:53:08.30
You know that that pipeline ends up in Vietnam.

1104
00:53:08.30 --> 00:53:09.18
Yeah.

1105
00:53:09.18 --> 00:53:14.50
So your detailer calls you on a whole phone in the BOQ.

1106
00:53:14.50 --> 00:53:17.34
And I think I was a lieutenant by this point.

1107
00:53:17.34 --> 00:53:18.14
Maybe not.

1108
00:53:18.14 --> 00:53:20.02
Senior lieutenant junior grade anyway.

1109
00:53:20.02 --> 00:53:24.22
I had two rooms and a private bath.

1110
00:53:24.22 --> 00:53:28.18
And you were in Kingsville in those?

1111
00:53:28.18 --> 00:53:28.90
I was.

1112
00:53:28.90 --> 00:53:30.74
Big, solid BOQs there.

1113
00:53:30.74 --> 00:53:32.98
Very nice.

1114
00:53:32.98 --> 00:53:37.30
But when you took a shower, the water was so bad,

1115
00:53:37.30 --> 00:53:39.30
the ground water.

1116
00:53:39.30 --> 00:53:41.82
It smelled like ancient sauerkraut.

1117
00:53:41.82 --> 00:53:43.14
Remember that?

1118
00:53:43.14 --> 00:53:44.90
It was awful.

1119
00:53:44.90 --> 00:53:47.90
At any rate, we were OK.

1120
00:53:47.90 --> 00:53:51.58
So at what point do you get assigned to go to the RAG for F-4?

1121
00:53:51.58 --> 00:53:54.90
Well, your detailer calls you on a whole phone of all things.

1122
00:53:54.90 --> 00:53:56.42
And put Tom Copell on.

1123
00:53:56.42 --> 00:53:59.50
He's in room B-7.

1124
00:53:59.50 --> 00:53:59.98
God comes in.

1125
00:53:59.98 --> 00:54:02.58
Hey, Tommy, you got a phone call.

1126
00:54:02.58 --> 00:54:04.02
It's my detailer again.

1127
00:54:04.02 --> 00:54:06.62
He said, Tom, we really want you in the A-6.

1128
00:54:06.62 --> 00:54:08.06
That's just for you.

1129
00:54:08.06 --> 00:54:09.46
Same as the B-52.

1130
00:54:09.46 --> 00:54:12.10
You have experience with offsets and everything else.

1131
00:54:12.10 --> 00:54:14.14
It's going to be perfect.

1132
00:54:14.14 --> 00:54:15.46
I said, I don't want that, Bob.

1133
00:54:15.46 --> 00:54:17.58
You know that.

1134
00:54:17.58 --> 00:54:20.22
Call me back next.

1135
00:54:20.22 --> 00:54:22.22
A series of phone calls.

1136
00:54:22.22 --> 00:54:25.14
The last one was the same thing.

1137
00:54:25.14 --> 00:54:27.58
Tom, you're perfect for the A-6.

1138
00:54:27.58 --> 00:54:30.94
By now, you probably looked around, talked around about it.

1139
00:54:30.94 --> 00:54:32.90
That's a heck of an airplane.

1140
00:54:32.90 --> 00:54:33.86
Yeah, I know, Bob.

1141
00:54:33.86 --> 00:54:36.42
I still want F-4.

1142
00:54:36.42 --> 00:54:37.90
OK.

1143
00:54:37.90 --> 00:54:39.22
Let me think about it.

1144
00:54:39.22 --> 00:54:42.18
And about a week later, a guy called me and said,

1145
00:54:42.18 --> 00:54:44.46
you have orders up there at Admin.

1146
00:54:44.46 --> 00:54:45.62
Big spring at that time.

1147
00:54:45.62 --> 00:54:46.58
I'm sorry.

1148
00:54:46.58 --> 00:54:49.94
Kingsville at that time was nowhere land.

1149
00:54:49.94 --> 00:54:52.30
And I did not have a car.

1150
00:54:52.30 --> 00:54:56.74
I said, it's up at the other end of the main drag,

1151
00:54:56.74 --> 00:55:02.62
the parallel hangar area.

1152
00:55:02.62 --> 00:55:04.38
Walk, walk, walk, walk, walk.

1153
00:55:04.38 --> 00:55:07.38
I said, well, first of all, I said, Fred, what do my orders

1154
00:55:07.38 --> 00:55:08.06
say?

1155
00:55:08.06 --> 00:55:09.02
I wouldn't look at them.

1156
00:55:09.02 --> 00:55:10.14
It's none of my business.

1157
00:55:10.14 --> 00:55:14.90
Oh, gentlemen, don't read each other's mail.

1158
00:55:14.90 --> 00:55:16.66
So I'll walk up there and hear what I had.

1159
00:55:16.66 --> 00:55:19.38
F-4 to Marar.

1160
00:55:19.38 --> 00:55:21.82
And the F-4, what year did the F-4 come out?

1161
00:55:21.82 --> 00:55:22.86
What year was that?

1162
00:55:22.86 --> 00:55:26.34
I think the first prototype flew in 58.

1163
00:55:26.34 --> 00:55:27.86
Is that right?

1164
00:55:27.86 --> 00:55:29.22
That sounds about right.

1165
00:55:29.22 --> 00:55:30.34
Just real quick.

1166
00:55:30.34 --> 00:55:31.06
All right.

1167
00:55:31.06 --> 00:55:33.34
So you go through all Air Force training.

1168
00:55:33.34 --> 00:55:34.86
You're a B-52 guy.

1169
00:55:34.86 --> 00:55:37.34
And then you CQ in the F-9?

1170
00:55:37.34 --> 00:55:37.74
Yeah.

1171
00:55:37.74 --> 00:55:40.50
What was that like?

1172
00:55:40.50 --> 00:55:42.70
I mean, they're worried that you can't even get aboard, right?

1173
00:55:42.70 --> 00:55:43.18
Yeah.

1174
00:55:43.18 --> 00:55:43.70
Yeah.

1175
00:55:43.70 --> 00:55:44.58
So what was that like?

1176
00:55:44.58 --> 00:55:48.30
Well, I guess my F-C-L-P was OK.

1177
00:55:48.30 --> 00:55:53.26
And when I first time out, F-C-L-P, I think, this is ball.

1178
00:55:53.26 --> 00:55:54.98
I mean, I can do this and so forth.

1179
00:55:54.98 --> 00:55:57.10
And the guy comes back and he says, well, you were this

1180
00:55:57.10 --> 00:55:58.50
and you were this and you were that.

1181
00:55:58.50 --> 00:55:59.22
That's amazing.

1182
00:55:59.22 --> 00:56:00.74
How do you know that?

1183
00:56:00.74 --> 00:56:02.74
And so forth.

1184
00:56:02.74 --> 00:56:03.66
That's LSOs.

1185
00:56:03.66 --> 00:56:07.02
They grade you accurately.

1186
00:56:07.02 --> 00:56:11.38
And their club, Dave knows this.

1187
00:56:11.38 --> 00:56:13.06
I was in LSO.

1188
00:56:13.06 --> 00:56:14.74
Oh, OK.

1189
00:56:14.74 --> 00:56:16.66
It's hard to get into their club.

1190
00:56:16.66 --> 00:56:20.98
And you can't really dispute what they tell you.

1191
00:56:20.98 --> 00:56:26.26
And after every F-C landing, he's in your ready room saying,

1192
00:56:26.26 --> 00:56:30.06
well, you started out high and so forth and so forth.

1193
00:56:30.06 --> 00:56:31.58
So you guys have now both thrown it.

1194
00:56:31.58 --> 00:56:33.38
I was wondering if I missed something,

1195
00:56:33.38 --> 00:56:35.50
but the term get aboard.

1196
00:56:35.50 --> 00:56:36.86
What does this mean?

1197
00:56:36.86 --> 00:56:38.50
Expand on it.

1198
00:56:38.50 --> 00:56:41.90
There are guys, I guess, who just say, you crazy?

1199
00:56:41.90 --> 00:56:42.94
I'm not going to do that.

1200
00:56:42.94 --> 00:56:45.54
I thought I didn't realize you had to do that.

1201
00:56:45.54 --> 00:56:47.34
Or I guess that's what happens.

1202
00:56:47.34 --> 00:56:51.78
Or they're just what used to be called the guys a plumber.

1203
00:56:51.78 --> 00:56:54.18
And he can't do it.

1204
00:56:54.18 --> 00:56:56.86
So get aboard means you actually qualify in the aircraft?

1205
00:56:56.86 --> 00:57:00.06
Yeah, get aboard is just language for can you land on the ship.

1206
00:57:00.06 --> 00:57:00.54
Right.

1207
00:57:00.54 --> 00:57:01.62
And god.

1208
00:57:01.62 --> 00:57:02.70
Most people can.

1209
00:57:02.70 --> 00:57:03.38
I didn't.

1210
00:57:03.38 --> 00:57:04.10
That's what I was missing.

1211
00:57:04.10 --> 00:57:04.42
Yeah.

1212
00:57:04.42 --> 00:57:05.14
And it's hard.

1213
00:57:05.14 --> 00:57:08.14
It's the phrase of, hey, is this guy going to be able to get a board?

1214
00:57:08.14 --> 00:57:10.02
Meaning can he land his plane on the boat?

1215
00:57:10.02 --> 00:57:10.34
Right.

1216
00:57:10.34 --> 00:57:12.26
What happens, I think, every now and then,

1217
00:57:12.26 --> 00:57:14.10
is you got guys to go through the whole pipeline.

1218
00:57:14.10 --> 00:57:17.42
Kerry calls is the last thing you do in training, traditionally.

1219
00:57:17.42 --> 00:57:19.18
And you could be great at all these things.

1220
00:57:19.18 --> 00:57:22.14
But if you can't get aboard, you're no good to the Navy.

1221
00:57:22.14 --> 00:57:22.66
That's right.

1222
00:57:22.66 --> 00:57:24.30
Because we land on boats.

1223
00:57:24.30 --> 00:57:24.70
And so.

1224
00:57:24.70 --> 00:57:25.20
Oh, yeah.

1225
00:57:25.20 --> 00:57:27.30
We're saying you have a P3.

1226
00:57:27.30 --> 00:57:29.34
Yeah, and fighters, exactly.

1227
00:57:29.34 --> 00:57:30.34
So is that what happens?

1228
00:57:30.34 --> 00:57:31.42
You get sent to P3s?

1229
00:57:31.42 --> 00:57:32.14
You get.

1230
00:57:32.14 --> 00:57:34.18
I mean, now you get sent to P3s.

1231
00:57:34.18 --> 00:57:36.10
You go to helicopters.

1232
00:57:36.10 --> 00:57:37.74
If you can't get aboard in a jet,

1233
00:57:37.74 --> 00:57:40.06
they're going to send you to some other non-tactical platform.

1234
00:57:40.06 --> 00:57:42.34
That's true.

1235
00:57:42.34 --> 00:57:44.62
I've been talking about this lately.

1236
00:57:44.62 --> 00:57:47.82
It seems like there are certain skill sets of people.

1237
00:57:47.82 --> 00:57:49.74
Some people just can't get through.

1238
00:57:49.74 --> 00:57:53.38
Like, for instance, when I was going through SEAL training,

1239
00:57:53.38 --> 00:57:57.62
I would say about one out of every 100 guys,

1240
00:57:57.62 --> 00:57:59.70
there's not going to be able to shoot a pistol well.

1241
00:57:59.70 --> 00:58:01.98
And they might actually not make it through the training

1242
00:58:01.98 --> 00:58:03.46
because they can't shoot a pistol.

1243
00:58:03.46 --> 00:58:04.50
They might be an athlete.

1244
00:58:04.50 --> 00:58:05.46
They might be great at everything.

1245
00:58:05.46 --> 00:58:06.06
They might be smart.

1246
00:58:06.06 --> 00:58:07.70
They can't shoot a pistol.

1247
00:58:07.70 --> 00:58:08.90
Close quarters combat.

1248
00:58:08.90 --> 00:58:10.46
There's a bunch of strict little things

1249
00:58:10.46 --> 00:58:12.14
that you have to follow.

1250
00:58:12.14 --> 00:58:14.46
And some people, I think that number is about four

1251
00:58:14.46 --> 00:58:15.98
out of every 100.

1252
00:58:15.98 --> 00:58:19.18
This is in basic SEAL training or SEAL qualification training

1253
00:58:19.18 --> 00:58:21.30
that they're just not going to get it.

1254
00:58:21.30 --> 00:58:23.94
They're just not bad people.

1255
00:58:23.94 --> 00:58:25.26
They do a lot of other things well,

1256
00:58:25.26 --> 00:58:26.62
but they just can't do that thing.

1257
00:58:26.62 --> 00:58:28.98
And it sounds like occasionally someone

1258
00:58:28.98 --> 00:58:31.34
that can fly a plane, someone that can land it on the airfield,

1259
00:58:31.34 --> 00:58:33.26
someone that can do the turns they need to do in the sky,

1260
00:58:33.26 --> 00:58:35.14
someone that understands the dynamics of it,

1261
00:58:35.14 --> 00:58:37.26
but they can't get aboard.

1262
00:58:37.26 --> 00:58:39.34
They can't land on that aircraft carrier.

1263
00:58:39.34 --> 00:58:40.38
And then it doesn't matter.

1264
00:58:40.38 --> 00:58:41.22
That's right.

1265
00:58:41.22 --> 00:58:47.06
No, it does matter because you were a top gun guy,

1266
00:58:47.06 --> 00:58:53.54
but I was an instructor at Meridian at the end of my career.

1267
00:58:53.54 --> 00:58:57.50
And I don't remember exactly how or what

1268
00:58:57.50 --> 00:58:59.14
that the guy said to me.

1269
00:58:59.14 --> 00:59:01.54
And then friendly is collegial way.

1270
00:59:01.54 --> 00:59:04.22
You know, if your students can't cut it,

1271
00:59:04.22 --> 00:59:05.46
it's not their fault.

1272
00:59:05.46 --> 00:59:07.26
It's your fault.

1273
00:59:07.26 --> 00:59:12.62
Because if this guy is not the sort of guy

1274
00:59:12.62 --> 00:59:16.70
we want for a tail hook, we'll find a place for him.

1275
00:59:16.70 --> 00:59:19.98
And he'll be valuable to the Navy.

1276
00:59:19.98 --> 00:59:21.78
So in the Air Force is the other way around.

1277
00:59:21.78 --> 00:59:25.90
It always felt to me like they were trying to get rid of you.

1278
00:59:25.90 --> 00:59:29.14
They were always rotten to you, except for one guy who

1279
00:59:29.14 --> 00:59:32.66
wound up being a, I think I put this in my list of stuff.

1280
00:59:32.66 --> 00:59:36.86
He wound up being a four-star general in NATO and Europe.

1281
00:59:36.86 --> 00:59:42.82
He maybe was personal self-esteem or self-confidence

1282
00:59:42.82 --> 00:59:43.82
or something like that.

1283
00:59:43.82 --> 00:59:45.26
He was very quiet and struck.

1284
00:59:45.26 --> 00:59:49.06
He was in T-38s and at Air Force Advanced.

1285
00:59:49.06 --> 00:59:50.30
Very laid back.

1286
00:59:50.30 --> 00:59:53.38
He'd say, Tom, come on left a little bit more.

1287
00:59:53.38 --> 00:59:55.06
Or, Tom, let me show you.

1288
00:59:55.06 --> 00:59:56.02
And he did.

1289
00:59:56.02 --> 00:59:57.18
And that was his last.

1290
00:59:57.18 --> 00:59:59.94
And they wouldn't talk to me for 10 minutes and stuff

1291
00:59:59.94 --> 01:00:00.62
like that.

1292
01:00:00.62 --> 01:00:02.46
But not because he didn't want to.

1293
01:00:02.46 --> 01:00:05.22
He'd just let you go until you made him a, no, no, no.

1294
01:00:05.22 --> 01:00:08.18
Let me show you something and stuff like that.

1295
01:00:08.18 --> 01:00:10.18
I'd say, but at any rate, they always

1296
01:00:10.18 --> 01:00:12.26
acted like they wanted to get ready or worse.

1297
01:00:12.26 --> 01:00:14.74
And the Navy, the kid doesn't make it.

1298
01:00:14.74 --> 01:00:18.66
He's been qualified by us in 16 different ways.

1299
01:00:18.66 --> 01:00:26.34
If he quits or wants to quit, it's your fault, not his.

1300
01:00:26.34 --> 01:00:30.22
And so we'll find a place for him in Helos.

1301
01:00:30.22 --> 01:00:33.94
And we have two guys there and stuff like that.

1302
01:00:33.94 --> 01:00:37.78
So where the heck were we?

1303
01:00:37.78 --> 01:00:39.22
So then you do get your orders.

1304
01:00:39.22 --> 01:00:40.86
You get your F-4 orders.

1305
01:00:40.86 --> 01:00:45.70
And I guess I kicked this whole tangent off just by the F-4

1306
01:00:45.70 --> 01:00:49.18
at the time was just like the ultimate beast.

1307
01:00:49.18 --> 01:00:50.94
The monster.

1308
01:00:50.94 --> 01:00:52.86
That's what I always called it.

1309
01:00:52.86 --> 01:00:56.58
And then I went to Mirar.

1310
01:00:56.58 --> 01:00:59.90
And I remembered this like it was yesterday.

1311
01:00:59.90 --> 01:01:02.34
Check in, do all that.

1312
01:01:02.34 --> 01:01:05.42
Going to find a place in the BOQ, forget it.

1313
01:01:05.42 --> 01:01:07.90
No chance.

1314
01:01:07.90 --> 01:01:12.38
I had to go find a place to live off base and whatnot.

1315
01:01:12.38 --> 01:01:16.86
But at any rate, VF-121 was the F-4 RAG at that time

1316
01:01:16.86 --> 01:01:21.02
and was the eastward end of the runway there.

1317
01:01:21.02 --> 01:01:26.58
And a couple of steps going through a narrow gate that

1318
01:01:26.58 --> 01:01:28.06
was always open.

1319
01:01:28.06 --> 01:01:31.86
And then F-4, you're looking at the tail,

1320
01:01:31.86 --> 01:01:33.26
up the pipes of this thing.

1321
01:01:33.26 --> 01:01:35.14
And I thought, oh my god, I forgot.

1322
01:01:35.14 --> 01:01:36.46
This is a monster.

1323
01:01:36.46 --> 01:01:37.50
I forgot.

1324
01:01:37.50 --> 01:01:39.90
And they had Marines working on them

1325
01:01:39.90 --> 01:01:42.98
because they were going to Denang or Chulai

1326
01:01:42.98 --> 01:01:49.26
to get shot full of holes and eventually abandoned over there.

1327
01:01:49.26 --> 01:01:52.98
And they took the radars out and put lead noses in them

1328
01:01:52.98 --> 01:01:53.78
at that place.

1329
01:01:53.78 --> 01:01:56.34
And basically went over the whole thing.

1330
01:01:56.34 --> 01:02:01.18
And they had Marines Mechs working on them there.

1331
01:02:01.18 --> 01:02:03.70
But I thought, oh my god, look at that thing.

1332
01:02:03.70 --> 01:02:06.26
And so that's the thing.

1333
01:02:06.26 --> 01:02:08.78
And then I walked to the end of the hangar.

1334
01:02:08.78 --> 01:02:13.18
And two F-4s taken the runway.

1335
01:02:13.18 --> 01:02:17.58
And VF-121 at that time was at that end, the east end,

1336
01:02:17.58 --> 01:02:18.30
of the runway.

1337
01:02:18.30 --> 01:02:23.18
And 99% of the time, the Mirroir took off to the west.

1338
01:02:23.18 --> 01:02:25.74
And two F-4s rolled out on the runway.

1339
01:02:25.74 --> 01:02:29.14
It was night and early morning, low coastal clouds and fog,

1340
01:02:29.14 --> 01:02:31.70
just like here.

1341
01:02:31.70 --> 01:02:32.98
This is at Miramar.

1342
01:02:32.98 --> 01:02:37.22
And they ran up.

1343
01:02:37.22 --> 01:02:38.90
And then they rolled.

1344
01:02:38.90 --> 01:02:40.30
And they firewalled.

1345
01:02:40.30 --> 01:02:42.58
And they went to Burner.

1346
01:02:42.58 --> 01:02:45.02
And then they disappeared into the mist.

1347
01:02:45.02 --> 01:02:50.02
I thought, oh my god, I am in over my head.

1348
01:02:50.02 --> 01:02:51.66
But you learn to do it.

1349
01:02:51.66 --> 01:02:53.18
And get good at it.

1350
01:02:53.18 --> 01:02:55.22
I got pretty good at it.

1351
01:02:55.22 --> 01:02:59.06
Although, you know, there's a thing about LSOs,

1352
01:02:59.06 --> 01:03:00.98
since you're here.

1353
01:03:00.98 --> 01:03:03.94
So the LSO is the grader, basically?

1354
01:03:03.94 --> 01:03:05.14
That's the landing signal officer.

1355
01:03:05.14 --> 01:03:06.70
You grade every landing.

1356
01:03:06.70 --> 01:03:07.70
That's right.

1357
01:03:07.70 --> 01:03:08.26
OK.

1358
01:03:08.26 --> 01:03:13.06
And you have to call Meepo on state for every landing,

1359
01:03:13.06 --> 01:03:15.14
VFR, IFR, anything else.

1360
01:03:15.14 --> 01:03:19.50
And he's the guy when you look up and they say,

1361
01:03:19.50 --> 01:03:25.26
one peak is worth 10,000 scans, scanning your panel,

1362
01:03:25.26 --> 01:03:28.78
instrument flying is something that's hard to understand

1363
01:03:28.78 --> 01:03:30.98
if you haven't done it.

1364
01:03:30.98 --> 01:03:33.18
You cannot make a mistake or you're

1365
01:03:33.18 --> 01:03:35.46
going to be killed and wreck the airplane.

1366
01:03:35.46 --> 01:03:39.98
No mistakes allowed in genuine IFR,

1367
01:03:39.98 --> 01:03:42.46
and especially carrier IFR.

1368
01:03:42.46 --> 01:03:49.06
But he's the guy who says to you, you say, 2400 Clara.

1369
01:03:49.06 --> 01:03:52.30
And he says to you, that means I don't see the Meepo.

1370
01:03:52.30 --> 01:03:54.70
And really, you can't see the deck either.

1371
01:03:54.70 --> 01:03:58.18
And he says to you, you're looking great, babe.

1372
01:03:58.18 --> 01:03:59.90
Keep it coming.

1373
01:03:59.90 --> 01:04:02.18
And you just have to trust what he's saying.

1374
01:04:02.18 --> 01:04:05.06
Because you can't see visually because of fog or whatever?

1375
01:04:05.06 --> 01:04:07.86
Well, one second later, or maybe a half second later,

1376
01:04:07.86 --> 01:04:11.26
you see the deck and then you're aboard.

1377
01:04:11.26 --> 01:04:14.62
He'll say that to you at a half mile.

1378
01:04:14.62 --> 01:04:17.58
The radar controller says, half mile, call a ball

1379
01:04:17.58 --> 01:04:19.58
or execute a wave off.

1380
01:04:19.58 --> 01:04:23.30
And you take a second peak and nothing there.

1381
01:04:23.30 --> 01:04:27.26
You see a white glow from the deck.

1382
01:04:27.26 --> 01:04:30.70
But if you're on centerline and on glide slope,

1383
01:04:30.70 --> 01:04:31.66
you're going to be OK.

1384
01:04:31.66 --> 01:04:33.62
And he's tracking that via radar?

1385
01:04:33.62 --> 01:04:36.50
Or he's because he can't see you either, right?

1386
01:04:36.50 --> 01:04:37.26
Yeah.

1387
01:04:37.26 --> 01:04:37.98
The ship does.

1388
01:04:37.98 --> 01:04:39.34
It's different now, I think.

1389
01:04:39.34 --> 01:04:41.46
But it's essentially sort of the same.

1390
01:04:41.46 --> 01:04:45.18
You have an IFR had a radar reflector on the nose gear.

1391
01:04:45.18 --> 01:04:48.58
And the ship's track while scan radar

1392
01:04:48.58 --> 01:04:50.74
would lock on to that receiver.

1393
01:04:50.74 --> 01:04:53.46
Otherwise, it might lock on to the wing tip.

1394
01:04:53.46 --> 01:05:00.30
And that will keep you on if you're flying accurately.

1395
01:05:00.30 --> 01:05:02.34
Everything will be when you break out.

1396
01:05:02.34 --> 01:05:06.26
You'll be on centerline on glide slope at the center of Neapol.

1397
01:05:06.26 --> 01:05:13.38
And basically, with a fuel in black oil ship,

1398
01:05:13.38 --> 01:05:16.46
Constellation was America before.

1399
01:05:16.46 --> 01:05:19.94
They were both black oil ships.

1400
01:05:19.94 --> 01:05:22.18
They have a stack gas problem.

1401
01:05:22.18 --> 01:05:25.30
But actually, with a nuclear powered carrier,

1402
01:05:25.30 --> 01:05:26.98
you have the bubble that comes around,

1403
01:05:26.98 --> 01:05:29.62
the wind coming around the island.

1404
01:05:29.62 --> 01:05:31.54
I'm told you can feel that too.

1405
01:05:31.54 --> 01:05:37.34
But with a fossil powered ship, you had a lot of bubble.

1406
01:05:37.34 --> 01:05:39.78
So you're hitting turbulence based on the rise of coming

1407
01:05:39.78 --> 01:05:40.14
to land.

1408
01:05:40.14 --> 01:05:41.34
Right there.

1409
01:05:41.34 --> 01:05:43.98
A tenth of a mile from touchdown.

1410
01:05:43.98 --> 01:05:44.98
Yeah.

1411
01:05:44.98 --> 01:05:47.46
One time, I had my mask loose.

1412
01:05:47.46 --> 01:05:50.26
You could smell it.

1413
01:05:50.26 --> 01:05:51.54
My mask wasn't tight enough.

1414
01:05:51.54 --> 01:05:51.94
What was it?

1415
01:05:51.94 --> 01:05:53.90
Do you remember your first carrier landing?

1416
01:05:53.90 --> 01:05:55.18
Yeah, I do.

1417
01:05:55.18 --> 01:05:57.34
How'd it go?

1418
01:05:57.34 --> 01:05:59.06
I thought that was pretty great.

1419
01:05:59.06 --> 01:05:59.98
That's all I remember.

1420
01:05:59.98 --> 01:06:02.66
I remember being on the catapult, though.

1421
01:06:02.66 --> 01:06:06.30
It was a Randolph with hydraulic cats.

1422
01:06:06.30 --> 01:06:09.26
It was one of the only ships left with hydraulic cats.

1423
01:06:09.26 --> 01:06:10.90
They'd all been converted to steam

1424
01:06:10.90 --> 01:06:13.78
when they put the angled deck on them.

1425
01:06:13.78 --> 01:06:17.86
These old Essex and Yorktown class ships,

1426
01:06:17.86 --> 01:06:19.62
they put steam catapults in them.

1427
01:06:19.62 --> 01:06:21.94
But some of them, they put hydraulic cats.

1428
01:06:21.94 --> 01:06:26.46
And Randolph was still a wonderful, clean, well run ship.

1429
01:06:26.46 --> 01:06:27.94
I thought a little.

1430
01:06:27.94 --> 01:06:29.74
I know the captain was very friendly to me,

1431
01:06:29.74 --> 01:06:31.22
because I was an oddball.

1432
01:06:31.22 --> 01:06:34.30
I was coming across Air Force Officer.

1433
01:06:34.30 --> 01:06:37.42
He had been told, come on up on the bridge.

1434
01:06:37.42 --> 01:06:38.74
It was very nice.

1435
01:06:38.74 --> 01:06:42.58
At any rate, sitting there, getting

1436
01:06:42.58 --> 01:06:45.86
ready to get on the hydraulic cats on Randolph,

1437
01:06:45.86 --> 01:06:50.98
I remember thinking to myself, I don't have to be doing this.

1438
01:06:50.98 --> 01:06:55.34
I remember thinking, if I say, I don't want to do this,

1439
01:06:55.34 --> 01:06:57.78
they'll stop right now.

1440
01:06:57.78 --> 01:06:59.94
I must be crazy.

1441
01:06:59.94 --> 01:07:00.58
I did it.

1442
01:07:00.58 --> 01:07:01.86
Boom.

1443
01:07:01.86 --> 01:07:02.26
But.

1444
01:07:02.26 --> 01:07:03.86
Without your first cat launch?

1445
01:07:03.86 --> 01:07:04.94
Yeah.

1446
01:07:04.94 --> 01:07:07.42
And they told you over and over again,

1447
01:07:07.42 --> 01:07:09.82
these are hydraulic cats.

1448
01:07:09.82 --> 01:07:13.82
Bob said, you're a pal and instructor.

1449
01:07:13.82 --> 01:07:17.66
He said, now, make sure you're all the way back.

1450
01:07:17.66 --> 01:07:20.42
Make sure you've got your elbow locked,

1451
01:07:20.42 --> 01:07:23.58
because it's a hell of a bang.

1452
01:07:23.58 --> 01:07:27.70
And you get, on your first 15, 20 feet,

1453
01:07:27.70 --> 01:07:30.98
you get 80% of your acceleration right up front.

1454
01:07:30.98 --> 01:07:33.18
And then you're sort of just trundled down

1455
01:07:33.18 --> 01:07:35.10
the rest of the way.

1456
01:07:35.10 --> 01:07:36.14
So I was ready.

1457
01:07:36.14 --> 01:07:39.42
But all the way back in the seat, head back,

1458
01:07:39.42 --> 01:07:43.30
and elbow locked, I didn't think about my knees.

1459
01:07:43.30 --> 01:07:48.42
When that thing went off, my knees were up here somewhere.

1460
01:07:48.42 --> 01:07:51.90
But the F9, I think the FAA team is the same way.

1461
01:07:51.90 --> 01:07:57.34
You can take the shot, hands off, and then grab the stick

1462
01:07:57.34 --> 01:08:00.46
as soon as you're out over the water.

1463
01:08:00.46 --> 01:08:03.02
So I still had my hand on the pole,

1464
01:08:03.02 --> 01:08:05.82
but I had to get my knees back down.

1465
01:08:05.82 --> 01:08:09.26
So is the hydraulic harder to launch than the steam,

1466
01:08:09.26 --> 01:08:11.22
because the steam is more gradual buildup or something?

1467
01:08:11.22 --> 01:08:12.90
Yeah, the steam is smoother.

1468
01:08:12.90 --> 01:08:15.70
And it's a continuous flow.

1469
01:08:15.70 --> 01:08:19.78
And I guess the new electric cats are that way as well.

1470
01:08:19.78 --> 01:08:21.38
It's supposed to be even better, I guess.

1471
01:08:21.38 --> 01:08:24.86
I don't know how there would be, but I guess there would be.

1472
01:08:24.86 --> 01:08:27.74
Now, this is the time like Dan Peterson,

1473
01:08:27.74 --> 01:08:31.62
you guys are working almost getting in this air to air

1474
01:08:31.62 --> 01:08:35.18
combat, where you're training at a level that really you

1475
01:08:35.18 --> 01:08:36.14
hadn't trained before.

1476
01:08:36.14 --> 01:08:38.90
Or the pilots hadn't been training this way.

1477
01:08:38.90 --> 01:08:43.30
We're going hard against each other all the time.

1478
01:08:43.30 --> 01:08:44.34
Yes and no.

1479
01:08:44.34 --> 01:08:48.78
In that, that was the beginning of the,

1480
01:08:48.78 --> 01:08:52.22
I said in my talking to Dave via email,

1481
01:08:52.22 --> 01:08:55.42
I said my only claim to fame here, being unusual,

1482
01:08:55.42 --> 01:08:58.10
if you will, is the fact that I was there

1483
01:08:58.10 --> 01:09:01.62
when what became Top Gun started.

1484
01:09:01.62 --> 01:09:02.62
I was there.

1485
01:09:02.62 --> 01:09:06.14
Sam Leeds, who's in Dan Peterson's book,

1486
01:09:06.14 --> 01:09:07.98
came into various ready rooms.

1487
01:09:07.98 --> 01:09:10.42
And VF-121 had about three or four of them,

1488
01:09:10.42 --> 01:09:13.46
I can't even remember because they took the whole hanger.

1489
01:09:13.46 --> 01:09:15.46
And they came in there and said, we're going to do that.

1490
01:09:15.46 --> 01:09:17.90
Oh, a lot of F-4s.

1491
01:09:17.90 --> 01:09:23.22
And some F-8s too, were getting shot down by MiG-17s mostly.

1492
01:09:23.22 --> 01:09:27.54
But RA-5Cs were getting shot down by MiG-21s

1493
01:09:27.54 --> 01:09:30.66
because they were MiG-21.

1494
01:09:30.66 --> 01:09:34.54
RA-5C would be cruising at, say, 600 knots, taking pictures,

1495
01:09:34.54 --> 01:09:37.06
or going to his next spot to take pictures.

1496
01:09:37.06 --> 01:09:42.10
And the MiG-21 would come downhill from 30, 35,000

1497
01:09:42.10 --> 01:09:46.26
at 1.2, 1.4, something like that.

1498
01:09:46.26 --> 01:09:51.62
And launch Soviet, what was the B model,

1499
01:09:51.62 --> 01:09:55.38
they had stolen from us, a sidewinder,

1500
01:09:55.38 --> 01:09:57.58
and shoot down the RA-5C.

1501
01:09:57.58 --> 01:09:58.58
That was the big deal.

1502
01:09:58.58 --> 01:10:01.86
Don't let your RA-5C, if you're the escort,

1503
01:10:01.86 --> 01:10:05.46
and I was lots of times, if you're the escort of the RA-5C,

1504
01:10:05.46 --> 01:10:09.14
don't let him get, you have to keep looking back and up there

1505
01:10:09.14 --> 01:10:13.94
and be prepared to turn into him for a head-on with a sparrow.

1506
01:10:13.94 --> 01:10:16.98
But at any rate, what was the question?

1507
01:10:16.98 --> 01:10:20.50
Well, I'm just trying to gather that eventually what I want

1508
01:10:20.50 --> 01:10:23.34
to know is how well prepared you were when you went

1509
01:10:23.34 --> 01:10:27.14
on deployment from a pilot.

1510
01:10:27.14 --> 01:10:29.18
So I was in the SEAL teams.

1511
01:10:29.18 --> 01:10:32.22
We would shoot so many rounds through our guns.

1512
01:10:32.22 --> 01:10:34.30
We would do so many immediate action drills.

1513
01:10:34.30 --> 01:10:39.62
We would do so many drills and so much training

1514
01:10:39.62 --> 01:10:42.90
that by the time we went overseas, I felt really good.

1515
01:10:42.90 --> 01:10:44.54
I felt really good.

1516
01:10:44.54 --> 01:10:49.18
And I'm trying to figure out where you guys would feel

1517
01:10:49.18 --> 01:10:52.98
the first time you get on your first combat mission.

1518
01:10:52.98 --> 01:10:55.66
Well, there's nothing quite like getting shot at the first time.

1519
01:10:55.66 --> 01:10:57.22
You do remember that.

1520
01:10:57.22 --> 01:11:00.90
But I remember the time they had some sort of an exercise

1521
01:11:00.90 --> 01:11:02.98
where we flew down the coast and back up again

1522
01:11:02.98 --> 01:11:07.74
and maybe went up as high as Hanoi and or more

1523
01:11:07.74 --> 01:11:11.54
the seaport that the Haifong went at the mouth of the river

1524
01:11:11.54 --> 01:11:16.22
up there and back and got aboard and came aboard.

1525
01:11:16.22 --> 01:11:16.90
Big exercise.

1526
01:11:16.90 --> 01:11:21.14
I remember looking out over northern part of South Vietnam

1527
01:11:21.14 --> 01:11:23.74
and over into Laos and all that red.

1528
01:11:23.74 --> 01:11:26.98
I thought, holy smoke, that's for real.

1529
01:11:26.98 --> 01:11:29.02
It's only every one and every six.

1530
01:11:29.02 --> 01:11:31.14
But you're not quite ready for that.

1531
01:11:31.14 --> 01:11:33.74
And the first time you actually see it going by,

1532
01:11:33.74 --> 01:11:37.26
it makes you an older man immediately, I think.

1533
01:11:37.26 --> 01:11:40.22
So wherever we are.

1534
01:11:40.22 --> 01:11:43.06
So you're training to get ready to get over there?

1535
01:11:43.06 --> 01:11:44.74
There's no way you're dog fighting?

1536
01:11:44.74 --> 01:11:45.22
Are you?

1537
01:11:45.22 --> 01:11:46.14
Oh, yeah.

1538
01:11:46.14 --> 01:11:46.98
Oh, yes.

1539
01:11:46.98 --> 01:11:48.18
Yeah, one on ones.

1540
01:11:48.18 --> 01:11:50.02
That's what you did in your training.

1541
01:11:50.02 --> 01:11:53.54
You left Miramar and went out over the water.

1542
01:11:53.54 --> 01:11:58.18
And the standard deal was your flight leader,

1543
01:11:58.18 --> 01:11:59.34
you're the wingman.

1544
01:11:59.34 --> 01:12:00.50
He kisses you off.

1545
01:12:00.50 --> 01:12:03.54
You both turn 30 degrees away and you

1546
01:12:03.54 --> 01:12:05.98
proceed until one guy turns in.

1547
01:12:05.98 --> 01:12:08.90
You can turn in immediately or you can wait.

1548
01:12:08.90 --> 01:12:11.94
If you're the younger guy, you wait until the older guy

1549
01:12:11.94 --> 01:12:14.78
finally turns in because he can't see you anymore.

1550
01:12:14.78 --> 01:12:19.14
You can barely see him and you know his eyeballs.

1551
01:12:19.14 --> 01:12:20.58
Not as good as yours.

1552
01:12:20.58 --> 01:12:22.58
But you turn in and make a head on it.

1553
01:12:22.58 --> 01:12:24.74
And then you can see his wings flash.

1554
01:12:24.74 --> 01:12:28.70
And he sees your wings flash and make a head on pass.

1555
01:12:28.70 --> 01:12:30.98
But that's not the way it is in combat.

1556
01:12:30.98 --> 01:12:35.74
When you get into a combat situation, well, statistically,

1557
01:12:35.74 --> 01:12:39.34
it doesn't matter whether it's World War I, Korea,

1558
01:12:39.34 --> 01:12:41.70
or the Vietnam War.

1559
01:12:41.70 --> 01:12:45.50
The guys who got shot down, the guys who didn't see it coming,

1560
01:12:45.50 --> 01:12:49.38
it's like 99% of them.

1561
01:12:49.38 --> 01:12:51.86
One guy got shot down, let's say.

1562
01:12:51.86 --> 01:12:55.02
He said, yeah, he got it on me and he pulled inside

1563
01:12:55.02 --> 01:12:57.06
and he unloaded and he got me.

1564
01:12:57.06 --> 01:12:58.62
But that's the exception.

1565
01:12:58.62 --> 01:13:01.74
And more over 95% of the airplane shot

1566
01:13:01.74 --> 01:13:09.34
then I popped a pee there in Vietnam with AAA,

1567
01:13:09.34 --> 01:13:10.82
not with SAMs.

1568
01:13:10.82 --> 01:13:12.98
Everybody knows SAMs this and SAMs that.

1569
01:13:12.98 --> 01:13:16.46
But no, when you're vulnerable and relatively close

1570
01:13:16.46 --> 01:13:20.10
to the ground, that's when they got you,

1571
01:13:20.10 --> 01:13:22.06
especially when you could see it going by you

1572
01:13:22.06 --> 01:13:24.22
or in the envelope if you will.

1573
01:13:24.22 --> 01:13:26.70
And that's just a matter of chance in a way.

1574
01:13:26.70 --> 01:13:27.30
That's right.

1575
01:13:27.30 --> 01:13:30.10
Well, better tactics.

1576
01:13:30.10 --> 01:13:33.54
There are better tactics and poorer tactics.

1577
01:13:33.54 --> 01:13:38.82
And I think I wrote in, is that my monograph there?

1578
01:13:38.82 --> 01:13:43.26
Guy said to me way back, in Kingsville,

1579
01:13:43.26 --> 01:13:47.38
I teach you to let it roll off on a wing, let the nose fall,

1580
01:13:47.38 --> 01:13:50.86
acquire the target, adjust a little bit,

1581
01:13:50.86 --> 01:13:55.26
and now you're watching the altimeter and so forth.

1582
01:13:55.26 --> 01:13:56.62
I said, this is baloney.

1583
01:13:56.62 --> 01:13:57.90
I want to hit the target.

1584
01:13:57.90 --> 01:14:00.98
I want to put them right in the hole there.

1585
01:14:00.98 --> 01:14:04.58
Pull down, up, invert, pull down.

1586
01:14:04.58 --> 01:14:06.86
Some ROs think you're crazy the first time

1587
01:14:06.86 --> 01:14:08.86
they're in the back when you do this.

1588
01:14:08.86 --> 01:14:12.02
Pull down as steep as possible.

1589
01:14:12.02 --> 01:14:15.06
Well, more than 30 degrees, you betcha.

1590
01:14:15.06 --> 01:14:18.14
How about 60 or 70 degrees?

1591
01:14:18.14 --> 01:14:22.34
The steeper you are, the safer you are, the faster you are,

1592
01:14:22.34 --> 01:14:23.66
the better you are.

1593
01:14:23.66 --> 01:14:25.26
And then I think I wrote in here.

1594
01:14:25.26 --> 01:14:29.42
Is there any compromise when you go to come out of that dive

1595
01:14:29.42 --> 01:14:32.34
and turn the airplane back up towards the sky?

1596
01:14:32.34 --> 01:14:36.90
Not really, because they've been through all that at Pax River.

1597
01:14:36.90 --> 01:14:42.58
Say the flight test in the book, the manual that you have,

1598
01:14:42.58 --> 01:14:47.94
the NATOPS manual, the flight manual for pilots,

1599
01:14:47.94 --> 01:14:50.94
or the tactics manual has all these tables in there.

1600
01:14:50.94 --> 01:14:54.94
And you can say, if I get out and let's say,

1601
01:14:54.94 --> 01:15:01.54
I have 80 degrees angle of dive and I get out at 6,000 feet,

1602
01:15:01.54 --> 01:15:03.46
I'll still be well clear.

1603
01:15:03.46 --> 01:15:08.82
I have 1,500 feet of to clear if I pull 6 and 1 half Gs

1604
01:15:08.82 --> 01:15:09.42
to get out.

1605
01:15:09.42 --> 01:15:12.14
If I pull 7, I'm even better off.

1606
01:15:12.14 --> 01:15:14.90
But you lose power when you do that.

1607
01:15:14.90 --> 01:15:17.70
I'm sorry, you lose airspeed when you do that.

1608
01:15:17.70 --> 01:15:20.74
So you pull the Gs, you're safe.

1609
01:15:20.74 --> 01:15:22.78
A lot of guys would not do that, though.

1610
01:15:22.78 --> 01:15:25.86
But did you train this way before going to Vietnam?

1611
01:15:25.86 --> 01:15:29.62
Did you know that the high angle attack was better?

1612
01:15:29.62 --> 01:15:31.06
No.

1613
01:15:31.06 --> 01:15:33.06
Were you figured out when you got there?

1614
01:15:33.06 --> 01:15:37.06
No, I figured it out in Arizona, going over there

1615
01:15:37.06 --> 01:15:40.18
to those targets that they have.

1616
01:15:40.18 --> 01:15:42.86
I guess in the East Coast, they have them all over the place,

1617
01:15:42.86 --> 01:15:44.30
too, in rural places.

1618
01:15:44.30 --> 01:15:49.50
It's a huge, plowed area, and plowed in a circle.

1619
01:15:49.50 --> 01:15:53.02
And they have two towers, wooden towers,

1620
01:15:53.02 --> 01:15:56.14
and 12 o'clock at 3 o'clock.

1621
01:15:56.14 --> 01:15:58.50
And they talk to each other.

1622
01:15:58.50 --> 01:16:01.86
And they tell you where your hit was on there.

1623
01:16:01.86 --> 01:16:04.94
And a white thing in the center.

1624
01:16:04.94 --> 01:16:07.38
And they tell you, you bomb.

1625
01:16:07.38 --> 01:16:12.74
But a guy told me, if you want to be safe, be steeper, be faster.

1626
01:16:12.74 --> 01:16:14.18
I said, that's for me.

1627
01:16:14.18 --> 01:16:17.94
And then I saw this picture, sort of famous.

1628
01:16:17.94 --> 01:16:21.30
And you've probably seen it of an airplane diving

1629
01:16:21.30 --> 01:16:25.82
on a Japanese aircraft carrier at midway.

1630
01:16:25.82 --> 01:16:28.98
And the guy is 89 degrees.

1631
01:16:28.98 --> 01:16:29.98
That is for me.

1632
01:16:29.98 --> 01:16:31.26
That's why I'm going to do it.

1633
01:16:31.26 --> 01:16:33.14
So roll inverted, pull into your nose down.

1634
01:16:33.14 --> 01:16:34.62
Then you get your dive right there.

1635
01:16:34.62 --> 01:16:37.34
Because your nose wants to come up the faster you go.

1636
01:16:37.34 --> 01:16:41.90
And an airplane, whether it's a Piper Cub or an F-4 or F-18,

1637
01:16:41.90 --> 01:16:46.02
your nose wants to rise as you build air.

1638
01:16:46.02 --> 01:16:48.06
Airspeed is just aerodynamics.

1639
01:16:48.06 --> 01:16:50.58
So get the nose down there right now.

1640
01:16:50.58 --> 01:16:52.58
And then you can do whatever you want.

1641
01:16:52.58 --> 01:16:56.58
F-4, you could pull a powered idle at 500.

1642
01:16:56.58 --> 01:16:57.82
And it would hold five.

1643
01:16:57.82 --> 01:17:00.06
I don't know what they do in F-18s.

1644
01:17:00.06 --> 01:17:02.58
But then anyway, pull a powered idle at 500,

1645
01:17:02.58 --> 01:17:06.54
almost no matter what your dive angle was.

1646
01:17:06.54 --> 01:17:09.18
What does that mean, pull powered idle at 500?

1647
01:17:09.18 --> 01:17:10.18
What does that mean?

1648
01:17:10.18 --> 01:17:13.22
Just pull the throttles all the way back to idle.

1649
01:17:13.22 --> 01:17:15.54
And it would hold 500 knots.

1650
01:17:15.54 --> 01:17:16.02
Got it.

1651
01:17:16.02 --> 01:17:18.58
So you wouldn't increase your speed to some.

1652
01:17:18.58 --> 01:17:18.94
Right.

1653
01:17:18.94 --> 01:17:20.62
I don't know why.

1654
01:17:20.62 --> 01:17:23.22
It's just they discovered it, no doubt,

1655
01:17:23.22 --> 01:17:26.30
after they were actually flying the airplane.

1656
01:17:26.30 --> 01:17:29.74
But if you go 550, it'll hold that.

1657
01:17:29.74 --> 01:17:32.22
So a lot of guys would say 500 is fast enough for me.

1658
01:17:32.22 --> 01:17:33.54
I've got to pull out of this.

1659
01:17:33.54 --> 01:17:35.22
But I said, Blaney, look on the charts.

1660
01:17:35.22 --> 01:17:36.82
You can get out easy.

1661
01:17:36.82 --> 01:17:37.94
They wouldn't do it.

1662
01:17:37.94 --> 01:17:39.86
But I said, steeper is better.

1663
01:17:39.86 --> 01:17:41.74
So I was surprised.

1664
01:17:41.74 --> 01:17:45.10
The guy in the back says, you know, we were 560 knots tonight.

1665
01:17:45.10 --> 01:17:46.98
Yeah, fine.

1666
01:17:46.98 --> 01:17:48.94
Like that.

1667
01:17:48.94 --> 01:17:50.78
I never got any holes.

1668
01:17:50.78 --> 01:17:52.54
I got scared a couple of times.

1669
01:17:52.54 --> 01:17:54.02
Well, yeah.

1670
01:17:54.02 --> 01:17:55.10
Got warned.

1671
01:17:55.10 --> 01:18:01.50
I had a load go off right there that gave me,

1672
01:18:01.50 --> 01:18:04.58
you know, a picture taken with an old style flash bulb.

1673
01:18:04.58 --> 01:18:07.62
It gave me spots in front of my eyes.

1674
01:18:07.62 --> 01:18:10.58
It was that close, but no holes.

1675
01:18:10.58 --> 01:18:12.54
I never did.

1676
01:18:12.54 --> 01:18:17.62
And the guys who came back with a hole about as big as a 45

1677
01:18:17.62 --> 01:18:22.30
caliber bullet in the bottom of the airplane, but not me.

1678
01:18:22.30 --> 01:18:30.26
We had leadership in the squadron I was in that I kept going back

1679
01:18:30.26 --> 01:18:34.66
to reading your book about how this guy, Ruel Gardner,

1680
01:18:34.66 --> 01:18:35.98
the way he operated.

1681
01:18:35.98 --> 01:18:37.98
And he was a former underwater demolition team guy.

1682
01:18:37.98 --> 01:18:38.98
Right.

1683
01:18:38.98 --> 01:18:42.02
And so how did he operate?

1684
01:18:42.02 --> 01:18:45.94
He was very laid back, very quiet about everything.

1685
01:18:45.94 --> 01:18:51.02
And we get after him about sharks, for instance.

1686
01:18:51.02 --> 01:18:54.22
And he said, nah, he says sharks don't bother you.

1687
01:18:54.22 --> 01:18:56.86
But barracudas sometimes do.

1688
01:18:56.86 --> 01:18:58.18
They're curious.

1689
01:18:58.18 --> 01:19:00.58
And they'll come right up to you and wonder what the heck you're

1690
01:19:00.58 --> 01:19:02.78
doing and what you are.

1691
01:19:02.78 --> 01:19:04.02
I didn't get it right.

1692
01:19:04.02 --> 01:19:05.54
That sort of thing.

1693
01:19:05.54 --> 01:19:10.94
And he was the guy who would do the classic Navy routine, if

1694
01:19:10.94 --> 01:19:11.54
you will.

1695
01:19:11.54 --> 01:19:13.70
Tom, can you help me with this?

1696
01:19:13.70 --> 01:19:16.10
As opposed to Tom, get that done.

1697
01:19:16.10 --> 01:19:20.70
Rather, can you help me with this?

1698
01:19:20.70 --> 01:19:24.02
It's funny in leadership terms.

1699
01:19:24.02 --> 01:19:27.66
If you say to a guy, can you help me with this?

1700
01:19:27.66 --> 01:19:31.58
He may not really want to do it.

1701
01:19:31.58 --> 01:19:35.94
But the way you phrase it makes you want to help him.

1702
01:19:35.94 --> 01:19:40.10
If he says, do that or else and you don't want to do it,

1703
01:19:40.10 --> 01:19:41.54
this is you all.

1704
01:19:41.54 --> 01:19:42.54
100%.

1705
01:19:42.54 --> 01:19:44.98
You know?

1706
01:19:44.98 --> 01:19:47.70
It's your style.

1707
01:19:47.70 --> 01:19:51.58
But it's effective in leadership terms.

1708
01:19:51.58 --> 01:19:56.94
Very effective to use the old Navy way of doing things like

1709
01:19:56.94 --> 01:19:57.18
that.

1710
01:19:57.18 --> 01:20:01.30
I don't know how the Marine Corps operates, but I had a pal who

1711
01:20:01.30 --> 01:20:06.90
got killed in Vietnam who's told me I will be a Marine general.

1712
01:20:06.90 --> 01:20:11.98
He got killed being aggressive, I think, based upon what I heard

1713
01:20:11.98 --> 01:20:13.78
about what happened with him.

1714
01:20:13.78 --> 01:20:22.18
But to that end, I just wondered how the Marine Corps operates

1715
01:20:22.18 --> 01:20:24.62
when the guy doesn't want to really do that.

1716
01:20:24.62 --> 01:20:29.22
But he would if you had just asked him as opposed to saying to

1717
01:20:29.22 --> 01:20:30.38
it or else.

1718
01:20:30.38 --> 01:20:34.18
Well, having worked with all kinds of leaders in the Army,

1719
01:20:34.18 --> 01:20:37.50
Navy, Air Force, and Marines, the good leaders in all those

1720
01:20:37.50 --> 01:20:40.42
organizations are the type that say, hey, I need some help with

1721
01:20:40.42 --> 01:20:40.58
this.

1722
01:20:40.58 --> 01:20:41.42
Hey, what do you think?

1723
01:20:41.42 --> 01:20:42.78
How do you think we should bet?

1724
01:20:42.78 --> 01:20:43.74
I think that's the stuff.

1725
01:20:43.74 --> 01:20:46.58
And across the board, and then you take this into the civilian

1726
01:20:46.58 --> 01:20:50.02
sector as well, the ones that Barch orders and yell at people

1727
01:20:50.02 --> 01:20:52.50
and say, you need to do this right now because I'm ordering you

1728
01:20:52.50 --> 01:20:53.02
to do it.

1729
01:20:53.02 --> 01:20:56.94
They're not ever considered to be good leaders.

1730
01:20:56.94 --> 01:21:00.10
But that's by and large the Air Force style.

1731
01:21:00.10 --> 01:21:01.66
No exaggeration.

1732
01:21:01.66 --> 01:21:05.50
Maybe my experience in the Air Force wasn't broad enough.

1733
01:21:05.50 --> 01:21:08.14
But by and large, that's what they do there.

1734
01:21:08.14 --> 01:21:09.26
What, Barch orders?

1735
01:21:09.26 --> 01:21:09.74
Yeah.

1736
01:21:09.74 --> 01:21:11.66
Yeah, that's unfortunate.

1737
01:21:11.66 --> 01:21:15.46
Maybe the order, having read his autobiography,

1738
01:21:15.46 --> 01:21:17.74
he didn't write it himself really, really.

1739
01:21:17.74 --> 01:21:21.58
But Ferris LeMay talking about the way

1740
01:21:21.58 --> 01:21:26.10
he operated in England in World War II, do it or else.

1741
01:21:26.10 --> 01:21:28.14
Wait a minute.

1742
01:21:28.14 --> 01:21:32.62
Yeah, well, there's a whole thing to talk about there.

1743
01:21:32.62 --> 01:21:35.06
There's this idea of the authoritarian people.

1744
01:21:35.06 --> 01:21:37.90
Certain people have an authoritarian mindset.

1745
01:21:37.90 --> 01:21:40.46
They're attracted to the authoritarian mindset.

1746
01:21:40.46 --> 01:21:42.70
And when they look at the military, when they're

1747
01:21:42.70 --> 01:21:45.34
10 years old or 17 years old or 20 years old,

1748
01:21:45.34 --> 01:21:46.78
they look at the military.

1749
01:21:46.78 --> 01:21:49.02
And they're very excited about it because they think, oh,

1750
01:21:49.02 --> 01:21:53.18
there's a place where if I have rank,

1751
01:21:53.18 --> 01:21:54.74
people have to respect me.

1752
01:21:54.74 --> 01:21:56.02
They have to listen to me.

1753
01:21:56.02 --> 01:21:59.86
And so the military actually attracts these type of people.

1754
01:21:59.86 --> 01:22:06.54
And most of the time, they kind of become not the best leaders.

1755
01:22:06.54 --> 01:22:09.10
And they usually don't make it very far because they

1756
01:22:09.10 --> 01:22:11.18
piss people off and whatever.

1757
01:22:11.18 --> 01:22:13.22
Occasionally, you'll have someone that

1758
01:22:13.22 --> 01:22:14.58
gets put in the right circumstances.

1759
01:22:14.58 --> 01:22:17.18
And despite the fact that they're a tyrannical leader,

1760
01:22:17.18 --> 01:22:18.54
they're still able to advance.

1761
01:22:18.54 --> 01:22:21.66
And Curtis LeMay is probably a good example of that.

1762
01:22:21.66 --> 01:22:24.94
Here he was in charge of bombing Europe.

1763
01:22:24.94 --> 01:22:26.02
And he puts together a plan.

1764
01:22:26.02 --> 01:22:27.94
It's like, hey, this is what we're doing.

1765
01:22:27.94 --> 01:22:30.18
And it was an extreme situation.

1766
01:22:30.18 --> 01:22:31.14
And it ended up working.

1767
01:22:31.14 --> 01:22:33.22
And then he gets his.

1768
01:22:33.22 --> 01:22:34.50
They made him a hero.

1769
01:22:34.50 --> 01:22:37.74
But in his autobiography, he says that I had no choice

1770
01:22:37.74 --> 01:22:41.78
but to begin to ascertain that we had to do it that way

1771
01:22:41.78 --> 01:22:44.98
or else we wouldn't do it at all.

1772
01:22:44.98 --> 01:22:46.34
So it can happen.

1773
01:22:46.34 --> 01:22:49.02
But like I said, I've worked with Air Force.

1774
01:22:49.02 --> 01:22:49.82
I've worked with Navy.

1775
01:22:49.82 --> 01:22:51.06
I've worked with the Marine Corps.

1776
01:22:51.06 --> 01:22:52.46
I've worked with the Navy.

1777
01:22:52.46 --> 01:22:56.26
And the good leaders and all of them are not tyrannical at all.

1778
01:22:56.26 --> 01:22:58.42
Now, are there situations that you can get into?

1779
01:22:58.42 --> 01:22:59.74
Or it's like, hey, we got it.

1780
01:22:59.74 --> 01:23:00.86
This is what we're doing.

1781
01:23:00.86 --> 01:23:03.38
Occasionally, that happens.

1782
01:23:03.38 --> 01:23:05.74
But it doesn't really happen a lot.

1783
01:23:05.74 --> 01:23:07.42
And yeah.

1784
01:23:07.42 --> 01:23:11.54
Now, I'm also thinking with your old job in the Air Force,

1785
01:23:11.54 --> 01:23:15.94
where you've got there's no room for any error

1786
01:23:15.94 --> 01:23:17.98
because you're dealing with nuclear weapons,

1787
01:23:17.98 --> 01:23:24.14
that probably emphasized that type of leadership more

1788
01:23:24.14 --> 01:23:26.02
than because the other thing about it,

1789
01:23:26.02 --> 01:23:28.62
authoritarian mindset is they don't do well in combat

1790
01:23:28.62 --> 01:23:30.62
situations oftentimes because they

1791
01:23:30.62 --> 01:23:32.18
have a very structured mind.

1792
01:23:32.18 --> 01:23:34.34
They have a very predetermined way of thinking.

1793
01:23:34.34 --> 01:23:36.50
So they get thrown something that they didn't expect

1794
01:23:36.50 --> 01:23:38.50
and they just fall apart.

1795
01:23:38.50 --> 01:23:40.78
You know, the person that's great in garrison,

1796
01:23:40.78 --> 01:23:44.02
that's great at keeping everyone great at doing inspections,

1797
01:23:44.02 --> 01:23:47.14
great at keeping everyone in the proper uniform,

1798
01:23:47.14 --> 01:23:49.42
they get into combat where all of a sudden the enemy gets

1799
01:23:49.42 --> 01:23:51.66
a vote and there's things happening they didn't expect.

1800
01:23:51.66 --> 01:23:52.70
And people are getting shot.

1801
01:23:52.70 --> 01:23:56.30
And a lot of times, those people don't do well

1802
01:23:56.30 --> 01:23:58.22
in combat scenarios.

1803
01:23:58.22 --> 01:24:01.06
Well, there's something about that that

1804
01:24:01.06 --> 01:24:04.50
just occurs to me right now is that on consolation

1805
01:24:04.50 --> 01:24:07.02
for that 10 month, 9 month cruise,

1806
01:24:07.02 --> 01:24:08.86
I never heard of that happening.

1807
01:24:08.86 --> 01:24:12.94
And you had two squadrons of A7s, two squadrons of A4s,

1808
01:24:12.94 --> 01:24:17.86
one squadron of A6s, a detachment of RA5Cs,

1809
01:24:17.86 --> 01:24:21.42
and combat helo squadron from Japan,

1810
01:24:21.42 --> 01:24:24.06
squadron, whatever they were.

1811
01:24:24.06 --> 01:24:28.78
I think there were two armored heavy duty helicopters

1812
